A VAN TRAILER CONTAINING HAZARDOUS WASTE WAS ENROUTE FROM YUASA EXCIDE LOCATED AT 12680 WEST CEDAR DRIVE IN LAKEWOOD, CO TO CLEAN HARBORS OF BRAINTREE, INC. LOCATED AT 385 QUINCY AVENUE IN BRAINTREE, MA. DURING A ROUTINE STOP AT SPRING GROVE RECOVERY, INC. LOCATED AT 4879 SPRING GROVE ANENUE IN CINCINNATI, OH IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT APPROXIMATELY 8 OUNCES OF MATERIAL HAD ESCAPED FROM THE TOP BUNG CAPS OF 3 CONTAINERS ONTO THE FLOOR OF THE VAN TRAILER WHERE IT WAS PREVENTED FROM ESCAPING TO THE ENVIRONMENT. FACILITY PERSONNEL IMMEDIATELY CONTAINED THE RELEASE AND ABSORBED ALL FREE LIQUIDS WITH SPEEDI DRY. AN INSPECTION OF THE CONTAINERS IDENTIFIED THAT THE RELEASE WAS CAUSED BY LOOSE CLOSURES ON THE DRUMS. AS A PRECAUTION, THE BUNG CAPS OF THE THREE CONTAINERS IN QUESTION WERE REPLACED. ALL CLEAN-UP DEBRIS GENERATED WAS PLACED INTO A SUITABLE CONTAINER PENDING OFF-SITE DISPOSAL AT A FULLY LICENSED WASTE MANAGEMENT FACILITY. PRIOR TO DEPARTURE FROM THE SHIPPER'S LOCATION, ALL CONTAINERS WERE INSPECTED AND NO EVIDENCE OF LEAKING WAS OBSERVED. DRIVERS WILL CONTINUE TO INSPECT EACH CONTAINER AS IT IS LOADED AND WILL CONTINUE TO TAKE APPROPRIATE ACTIONS IN THE EVENT A CONTAINER IS FOUND TO BE LEAKING OR DAMAGED.

column168: A VAN TRAILER CONTAINING HAZARDOUS MATERIALS WAS ENROUTE FROM A HOUSEHOLD HAZARDOUS WASTE COLLECTION EVENT LOCATED AT 4545 CREEK ROAD IN CINCINNATI, OH TO CLEAN HARBORS SERVICES, INC. LOCATED AT 11800 SOUTH STONEY ISLAND AVENUE IN CHICAGO, IL. DURING A ROUTINE STOP AT SPRING GROVE RESOURCE RECOVERY, INC. LOCATED AT 4879 SPRING GROVE AVENUE IN CINCINNATI, OH IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT APPROXIMATELY 2 OUNCES OF MATERIAL HAD ESCAPED FROM HTE BOTTOM OF A CUBIC YARD FIBERBOARD BOX ONTO THE FLOOR OF THE VAN TRAILER WHERE IT WAS PREVENTED FROM ESCAPING TO THE ENVIRONMENT. AT THE TIME OF THE DISCOVERY, FACILITY PERSONNEL WERE IN THE PROCESS OF TRANSFERRING THE CONTAINERS ONTO A SECOND VAN TRAILER FOR CONTINUING TRANSPORTATION. ** UPON DISCOVERY OF THE RELEASE, FACILITY PERSONNEL CONTAINED THE RELEASE AND ABSORBED ALL FREE LIQUID WITH SPEEDI DRY. THE DAMAGED CONTAINER WAS INSPECTED AND IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE COVER OF ONE OF THE INDIVIDUAL PAINT CANS PACKAGED WITHIN THE BOX HAD DISLODGED ALLOWING MATERIAL TO SATURATE THE FIBERBOARD WALL OF THE PACKAGE. THE CONTENTS OF THE DAMAGED CONTAINER WERE RE-PACKAGED INTO A NEW CUBIC YARD BOX ALONG WITH ALL CLEAN-UP DEBRIS AND WAS SENT FOR DISPOSAL TO THE WASTE MANAGEMENT FACILITY INDICATED ON THE ORIGINAL SHIPPING DOCUMENT. ** IN ORDER TO PREVENT A RECURRENCE, INDIVIDUALS RESPONSIBLE FOR PACKAGING CONTAINERS IN THE FIELD HAVE BEEN RE-INSTRUCTED TO INSURE THAT ALL INNER CONTAINERS ARE PROPERLY SEALED AND SUFFICIENT ABSORBENT MATERIAL IS UTILIZED TO BOTH CUSHION THE INNER PACKAGES AS WELL AS ABSORB ANY LIQUID IN THE EVENT A CONTAINER OPENS DURING TRANSPORTATION.

column168: A VAN TRAILER CONTAINING HAZARDOUS WASTE WAS ENROUTE FROM STOLLE CORPORATION LOCATED AT 1501 MICHIGAN ST IN SIDNEY, OH TO CLEAN HARBORS SERVICES, INC. LOCATED AT 11800 SOUTH STONEY ISLAND AVE IN CHICAGO, IL. DURING A ROUTINE STOP AT SPRING GROVE RESOURCE RECOVERY, INC. LOCATED AT 4879 SPRING GROVE AVE IN CINCINNATI, OH IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT APPROXIMATELY 1/2 GALLON OF PAINT HAD ESCAPED FROM THE BOTTOM OF ONE OF THE DRUMS ONTO THE FLOOR OF THE VAN TRAILER WHERE IT WAS PREVENTED FROM ESCAPING TO THE ENVIRONMENT.  FACILITY PERSONNEL IMMEDIATELY CONTAINED THE RELEASE, ABSORBED ALL FREE LIQUIDS WITH SPEEDI DRY AND PLACED THE DAMAGED CONTAINER INTO A SUITABLE SALVAGE DRUM.  AN INSPECTION OF THE CONTAINER INDICATES THAT THE RELEASE CAN BE ATTRIBUTED TO THE DRUM BEING PLACED ONTO A SHARP OBJECT WHICH CREATED THE PINHOLE LEAK.  ALL CLEAN UP DEBRIS GENERATED AS A RESULT OF THE RELEASE WAS PLACED INTO THE SALVAGE DRUM AND WAS DISPOSED OF AT THE WASTE MANAGEMENT FACILITY INDICATED ON THE ORIGINAL SHIPPING DOCUMENT. PRIOR TO DEPARTURE FROM THE SHIPPER'S LOCATION, ALL CONTAINERS WERE INSPECTED AND NO EVIDENCE OF LEAKING WAS OBSERVED. DRIVERS WILL CONTINUE TO INSPECT EACH CONTAINER AS IT IS LOADED AND WILL CONTINUE TO TAKE APPROPRIATE ACTIONS IN THE EVENT A CONTAINER IS FOUND TO BE LEAKING OR DAMAGED.  IN ADDITION, LOADING PERSONNEL WILL BE RE-INSTRUCTED TO INSURE THAT CONTAINER STAGING AREAS, PALLETS AND/OR VAN TRAILER FLOORS ARE FREE OF ANY FOREIGN OBJECT WHICH COULD DAMAGE THE STRUCTURAL INTEGRITY OF A CONTAINER.

A VAN TRAILER CONTAINING HAZARDOUS WAS ENROUTE FROM CLEAN HARBORS OF CLEVELAND, INC. LOCATE AT 2900 BROADWAY IN CLEVELAND, OH TO CLEAN HARBORS OF BALTIMORE, INC. LOCATED AT 1910 RUSSELL STREET IN BALTIMORE, MD. DURING THE COURSE OF THE TRIP, THE DRIVER CONDUCTED A ROUTINE TIRE AND LOAD CHECK AND DISCOVERED THAT APPROXIMATELY 1 GALLON OF MATERIAL HAD ESCAPED FROM A PINHOLE LEAK THAT HAD DEVELOPED ON THE BOTTOM OF ONE OF THE CONTAINERS ONTO THE ASPHALT PARKING AREA WHERE THE DRIVER HAD STOPPED HIS VEHICLE. THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY CONTAINED THE RELEASE USING SPEEDI DRY AND CONTACTED HIS HOME DISPATCHER FOR ASSISTANCE WHO, IN TURN, DISPATCHED AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CREW FROM CLEAN HARBOR'S DEPTFORD, NJ SERVICE CENTER. IN ADDITION, CLEAN HARBORS CONTACTED THE NEW JERSEY DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION'S EMERGENCY RESPONSE LINE TO INFORM THEM OF THE RELEASE. UPON ARRIVAL AT THE SCENE, THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE CREW TRANSFERRED THE PRODUCT FROM THE LEAKING CONTAINER INTO A NEW DRUM. ALL CLEAN-UP DEBRIS GENERATED AS A RESULT OF THE CLEAN UP ACTIVITIES WAS CONTAINERIZED AND SENT FOR DISPOSAL ALONG WITH THE EMPTY DAMAGED CONTAINER TO THE INTENDED WASTE MANAGEMENT FACILITY INDICATED ON THE SHIPPING PAPER. ** PRIOR TO DEPARTURE FROM THE SHIPPER'S LOCATION, ALL CONTAINERS WERE INSPECTED AND NO EVIDENCE OF LEAKING WAS OBSERVED. DRIVERS WILL CONTINUE TO INSPECT EACH CONTAINER AS IT IS LOADED AND WILL CONTINUE TO TAKE APPROPRIATE ACTIONS IN THE EVENT A CONTAINER IS FOUND TO BE LEAKING OR DAMAGED.
LID ON DRUM WAS NOT SEALED AND A SMALL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT WAS LOST. THE MATERIAL EVAPORATED AND THE LID WAS PROPERLY SEALED. THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED AND THE FREIGHT WAS FORWARDED TO DESTINATION.
DRIVER WAS AT CONSIGNEE DOCK AND A RELEASE AROUND THE FITTING WAS DETECTED. THE CONSIGNEE ACCEPTED FREIGHT WITH NOTIFICATION ON BILL.

column168: ON 9-15-96 AT 11:30 AM, OUR DRIVER, LEHN D. THOMAS HAD A SPILL AT HARNED'S BOB MINIMARKET 102 CLAY DRIVE QUEENSTOWN, MD 21658 -  OUR DRIVER WAS IN OUR COMPANY TRUCK #58/TRAILER #30. HE WAS UNLOADING THE GASOLINE IN THE TRAILER. HE DIDN'T FOLLOW PROPER UNLOADING PROCEDURES WHEN SAW THAT THE FITTING WAS "BUBBLING" HE UN-DID THE VAPOR HOSE -- HE FORGOT TO UNHOOK THE DRAIN HOSE FIRST! HE ALSO DIDN'T DRAIN THE VAPOR HOSE PROPERLY. THERE WAS A BUBBLE IN THE TANK AND THE PRESSURE CAUSED A SMALL AMOUNT TO SPILL OUT OF THE VAPOR FITTING. WHEN HE SAW THIS HAPPENING HE IMMEDIATELY SHUT OFF ALL THE VALVES. LEHN THOMAS MET WITH SAFETY COMMITTEE MEMBERS ON 9-16-96. HE WAS WRITTEN & VERBALLY REPRIMANDED. DUE TO THE SERIOUSNESS OF NOT FOLLOWING PROPER PROCEDURE HE WILL BE RE-TRAINED AND TAKEN OFF DUTY FOR 3 DAYS. ** HARDESTY & SON, INC., TAKES HAZARDOUS MATERIAL INCIDENTS VERY SERIOUSLY. WE WILL CONTINUE TO HAVE OUR SAFETY MEETINGS ON A REGULAR BASIS. WE WILL ALSO PERSONALLY VERIFY THAT EACH & EVERY DRIVER IS TRAINED PROPERLY IN THIS AREA. WE WANT TO ENSURE THAT THIS DOES NOT HAPPEN AGAIN.

column168: DESCRIPTION OF EVENTS RELATING TO HAZARDOUS MATERIAL SPILL OF ORGANIC PEROXIED TYPE C LIQUID-BOOKING NUMBER HOUKAO 6370001.  CARGO ARRIVED CAROTRANS LOS ANGELES DOCK THE MORNING OF 9-10-96 ON A RAIL BOX FROM CAROTRANS HOUSTON.  WE BEGAN TO UNLOAD RAIL BOX AT APPROXIMATLEY 1:00 PM ON 9-10-96.  ON OPENING DOORS OF RAIL BOX WE NOTED THAT CARGO WAS BLOCKED AND BRACED BUT THERE WAS NO DUNNAGE BETWEEN PALLETS OF CARGO OR WALLS OF TRAILER.  ALL CARGO APPEARED SECURE AND IN GOOD ORDER.  WHEN WE ATTEMPTED TO REMOVE THE FIRST PALLET OF CARGO FROM THE RAIL BOX POSITIONED AT REAR OF TRAILER ON RIGHT HAND SIDE LOOKING INTO BOX THE FORKLIFT DRIVER NOTICED LIQUID FLOWING FROM PALLER ONTO FLOOR OF DOCK AT IMMEDIATE REAR OF TRUCK. FORKLIFT OPERATOR IMMEDIATELY SHUT DOWN FORKLIFT.  CLEANED DOCK OF PERSONNEL AND CONTACTED SUPERVISOR.  SUPERVISOR TOOK NOTE OF DAMAGED CARGO AND WENT TO EMERGENCY RESPONSE GUIDEBOOK FOR INSTRUCTION ON PROPER HANDLING.  DAMAGED PACKAGE WAS PLACED IN A HAZARDOUS RECOVERY DRUM AND AREA WAS CLEANED UP WITH AN INERT DAMP NON-COMBUSTIBLE MATERIAL AND PLACED IN SAME RECOVERY DRUM.  WER SIMULTANEOUSLY CALLED CHEMTREX, WHO CONTACTED THE SHIPPER, ELF ATOCHEM WHO THEN CONTACTED US.  AFTER REVIEWING THE PROCEDURES WE WERE TAKING WITH ELF ATOCHEM THEY ADVISED US WE WERE HANDLING CORRECTLY AND THERE WAS NOTHING ELSE NEEDED DONE.  WE ARE CURRENTLY WAITING FOR THE SHIPPER TO GIVE US WRITTEN DISPOSITION ON THE DAMAGE CARGO.  AFTER CLEAN UP OF AREA WE EXAMINED THE TRAILER TO DETERMINE CAUSE OF PUNCTURE AND DISCOVERED THAT A METAL STRIP RUNNING FROM THE FLOOR TO THE CEILING OF THE TRAILER HAD BEEN BROKEN LOOSE AND WAS PROTRUDING. THIS PROTRUSION WAS NOT VISIBLE WHEN WE TRIED TO UNLOAD THE PALLET BECAUSE THE PALLET HAD BEEN PUSHED FLUSH AGAINST TRAILER WAL OBSTRUCTING VIEW OR EVIDENCE OF PROTRUSION.  THE TRAILER SHOULD HAVE BEEN REPAIRED BEFORE LOADING.  PROPRER INSPECTION BY THE LOADING TERMINAL IN HOUSTON WOULD HAVE REVEALED THAT THE SHEET OF METAL RUNNING FROM THE FLOOR TO THE CEILING OF THE TRAILER WAS BROKEN AND PROTRUDING AND COULD HAVE BEEN CUT OFF OR RE-ATTACHED PROPERLY. CARDBOARD DUNNAGE COULD HAVE BEEN USED TO SEPARATE THE PALLETS FROM THE SIDE OF THE TRAILER.

column168: TRUCK WAS HEADED EAST BOUND ON I-70 BUSINESS LOOP.  THE TRUCK WAS TRAVELING AT APPROXIMATELY 50 MPH. A CAR APPROACHING FROM THE SOUTH ON 31 1/2 ROAD ROLLED INTO THE INTERSECTION AND HIT THE RIGHT SIDE OF OUR SEMI TRAILER, JUST AT THE REAR OF THE LANDING LEGS.  THE CAR KNOCKED THE BOTTOM LOAD PIPING OFF OF THE TRAILER. ALL FIRE VALVE SEALED, SO NO GASOLINE WAS SPILLED FROM THE CARGO TANK. HOWEVER, THE GASOLINE THAT WAS IN THE BOTTOM LOAD PIPING DID SPILL. THE GASOLINE WAS PUMPED OUT ANOTHER TRAILER.  THE SPILLED GASOLINE WAS ABSORBED WITH SORBANT MATERIAL AND DISPOSED OF IN ACCORDANCE WITH ALL APPLICABLE REGULATION.

AFTER IMMEDIATE DANGER WAS HANDLED BY LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT, IT WAS THEN INSPECTED AND DETERMINED WAS MADE THAT METAL VALVE AT THE BOTTOM OF THE TOTE HAD BEEN CORRODED AWAY BY THE CORROSIVE MATERIAL LOADED INTO THE TOTE, ULTIMATELY CAUSING THE VALVE TO COMPLETELY FAIL AND OPEN UP, POURING 330 GALLONS OF MATERIAL OUT. SAMSELL SERVICE WAS CONTACTED TO RESPONSE TO THE CLEAN UP AND REMEDIATION PROCES OF CLEANING APPROXIMATELY A 100 x 300 AREA ALONG WITH THE CLEAN UP AND REMEDIATION OF THE UNIT AND FREIGHT CONTENTS.  TWO EMPLOYEES COMPAINED TO HAVE COME INTO CONTCT BY INHALATION, ONE WAS HOSPITALIZED OVERNIGHT AND ONE WAS TREATED AND RELEASED THE SAME DAY. OHIO P.U.C.O. ALONG WITH THE OHIO E.P.A. WHERE ON THE SCENE AND CONDUCTED THEIR INVESTIGATION.  IT HAD BEEN DETERMINED BY THE P.U.C.O. AND OHIO E.P.S. THAT THE RESPONSIBLE PARTY FOR THIS INCIDENT BELINGS TO BRENT AMERICA LAKE BLUFF ILLINOIS
DRIVER PUMP UNLOADING.  PUMP LEAKED DRIVER TIGHTENED UP THE PACKING. CATCHING PRODUCT IN BUCKET AND BUCKET OVERFILLED.

column168: ON SEPT. 21, 1996 CECIL JENKINS WAS PROCEEDING NORTH ON HWY. 43, AXIS, ALABAMA. VEHICLE #1 STRUCK VEHICLE #2 ON RIGHT REAR, LOST CONTROL AND OVERTURNED.

THE DRUM WAS PUNCTURED BY A FORKLIFT BLADE WHILE IT WAS BEING UNLOADED FROM A SEMITRAILER ONTO THE FREIGHT DOCK. THE LIQUID WAS QUICKLY CONTAINED AND NEUTRALIZED WITH COPIUS AMOUNTS OF WATER. THE DRUM WAS PLACED IN AN OVERPACKED AND SHIPPED TO THE CONSIGNEE FOR DISPOSITION. CORRECTIVE ACTION HAD BEEN TAKEN WITH THE FORKLIFT OPERATOR AND THE RULES AND REGULATIONS FOR SAFE FORKLIFT OPERATION HAVE BEEN REVIEWED WITH ALL DOCK EMPLOYEES.

column168: DRIVER PICKED UP SHIPMENT AT OWENS CORNING. HE THEN PROCEEDED TO THE COY TERMINAL. ON TUESDAY, SEPTEMBER 17, 1996, DELTA DISTRIBUTORS, INCORPORATED DRIVER WILLIE FORD WAS ON HIS WAY TO A CUSTOMER.  THE DRIVER WAS MAKING A LEFT HAND TURN AND ANOTHER CAR WAS TURNING AT THE SAME TIME ON THE TRUCK DRIVERS SIDE.  THE TRUCK DRIVER HIT HIS BRAKES AND LOST CONTROL.  A SIDE DOOR CAME OPEN AND THE TANK FELL OUT.  THE LOUISIANA STATE POLICE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL UNIT AND THE LOUISIANA DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY WERE NOTIFIED AND DISPATCHED TO THE ACCIDENT SCENE.  BOTH DEPARTMENTS WITNESSED THE NEUTRALIZATION AND SPILL CLEAN UP.  ESTIMATED LOSS:  160 GALLONS OF 50% SODIUM HYDROXIDE/50% WATER RELEASED 1024 POUNDS OF SODIUM HYDROXIDE.  ALL DRIVERS RE-EDUCATED AND MADE AWARE OF USING ENOUGH SECURING DEVICES IN ORDER TO HOLD LOADS PROPERLY IN PLACE AND SIDE DOORS REWORKED ALSO.  SEE COPY OF ATTACHED CLEAN UP ACTION.
column172: Container, no description given (do not use if at all possible)

column168: AS OUR DRIVER WAS EN ROUTE FROM GLENMONT, NY, TO ACUSHNET, MASS, THE BOTTOM FILL VALVE AT THE REAR OF THE TRAILER VIBRATED OPEN.  DUE TO RAINY, MISTY WEATHER CONDITIONS, THE ESCAPING LIQUID NITROGEN PRODUCED A VAPOR CLOUD BEHIND THE TRAILER.  THE DRIVER NOTICED THE VAPOR AND ATTEMPTED TO CLOSE THE VALVE.  DUE TO THE ACCUMULATED ICE BUILDUP AROUND THE VALVE, THE DRIVER WAS UNABLE TO CLOSE IT.  THE LOCAL POLICE AND FIRE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED TO THE SCENE AND, WITH ASSISTANCE FROM OUR DRIVER AND EMERGENCY HAZMAT PERSONNEL, THE VALVE WAS SUCCESSFULLY CLOSED.  UPON COMPLETION OF THE TRIP, THE VALVE WAS INSPECTED BY OUR MAINTENANCE PERSONNEL.  NO DEFECTS WERE FOUND.  IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE VALVE WAS NOT TIGHTLY CLOSED AT THE BEGINNING OF THE TRIP.  ALL PERSONNEL HAVE BEEN INFORMED OF THIS INCIDENT AND INSTRUCTED ON THE IMPORTANCE OF SECURELY TIGHTENING ALL VALVES.

PRODUCT HAS SLOSHED OUT OF THAT HOLE AND ONTO THE FLOOR DURING TRANSIT FROM KANSAS CITY WAREHOUSE.  WHEN BUNG WAS REPLACED AND PALLET WAS REMOVED FROM TRAILER, IT WAS NOTICED THAT THE PALLET WAS COVERED WITH FLOOR-DRY.  SINCE THERE WAS NO FLOOR-DRY ON TRAILER FLOOR, IT MUST HAVE BEEN APPLIED IN K.C. PRIOR TO LOADING.  CAUTION SHOULD BE USED WHEN FILLING DRUMS WITH ACID TO INSURE PROPER BUNGS WILL BE REPLACED.  ACID DRUMS SHOULD BE INSPECTED AND ALL LEAKS TAKEN CARE OF PRIOR TO LOADING ON TRAILER.

ON SEPTEMBER 3, 1996, AT APPROXIMATELY 1115 HOURS, NATX 38525, LOAD, WAS OBSERVED LEAKING FROM THE DOME AREA WHILE BEING SWITCHED AT KCS' BATON ROUGE YARD.  THE TANK CAR WAS IMMEDIATELY ISOLATED TO THE YARD STORAGE TRACK TO PREVENT FURTHER MOVEMENT AND POSSIBLE LEAKAGE.  PATTY KING, WITH LOUISIANA STATE POLICE, WAS NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT AT 1215 HOURS.  THE SHIPPER, EXXON CHEMICAL AMERICAS, DISPATCHED REPAIR PERSONNEL WHO DETERMINED THE CAUSE OF THE LEAK TO BE A LEAKING INDUCTION VALVE FITTING, LOCATED AT THE TOP OF THE CAR, AND COMPLETED THE NECESSARY REPAIRS TO PREVENT FURTHER LEAKAGE AT 1220 HOURS.  THE TANK CAR WAS SUBSEQUENTLY RELEASED FOR DESTINATION AT 1253 HOURS.

DRIVER DID ADDITIONAL CLEANUP AND TURNED THE DRUM UPSIDE DOWN TO AVOID FURTHER LEAKAGE.  DRIVER HAS BEEN REPRIMANDED FOR HIS LACK OF PROPERLY IDENTIFYING CAUSE OF LEAK AFTER IT WAS INITIALLY NOTICED.  WAREHOUSE MANAGER HAS BEEN ADVISED OF THE SITUATION AND THE CONSEQUENCES OF IMPROPER SHIPPING TECHNIQUES.

THIS SHIPMENT WAS TENDERED TO OUR COMPANY BY VALLEY WAREHOUSING OF FDL, INC., ON SEPTEMBER 16, 1996.  THE FREIGHT WAS SCHEDULED TO DELIVER TO PEGLER-SYSCO FOOD SERVICES, COMPANY IN LINCOLN, NE. ON SEPTEMBER 18, 1996. THE SHIPMENT CONTAINED RESTAURANT SUPPLIES, WHICH INCLUDED GLASSWARE, PAPER PRODUCTS, LATEX GLOVES, COFFEE POTS, CANNED GOODS, ETC. AS WELL AS CLEANING SUPPLIES THAT WERE CONSIDERED HAZARDOUS MATERIAL. *******  ON SEPTEMBER 18, 1996 AT APPROXIMATELY 0600, OUR DRIVER WAS TRAVELING WEST ON NEBRASKA INTERSTATE I-80 WHEN SHE HEARD THREE SMALL EXPLOSIONS COMING FROM THE TRAILER SHE WAS PULLING.  AFTER HEARING THE EXPLOSIONS, THE DRIVER PULLED OFF ONTO EXIT RAMP 426 TO INVESTIGATE WHAT SHE HAD HEARD.  THE DRIVER DISCOVERED FLAMES COMING FROM AROUND THE AREA OF THE FIFTH WHEEL OF THE TRACTOR.  THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY OBTAINED HER FIRE EXTINGUISHER AND ATTEMPTED TO EXTINGUISH THE FIRE.  WHILE WORKING ON THE FIRE AN ACE HARDWARE TRUCK DRIVER STOPPED TO ASSIST AND USED HIS FIRE EXTINGUISHER TO ATTEMPT TO EXTINGUISH THE FIRE.  A CAR ALSO STOPPED AND THE DRIVER UTILIZED THEIR CAR PHONE TO CONTACT THE FIRE DEPARTMENT.  THE DRIVER WAS NOT ABLE TO UNHOOK THE TRACTOR FROM THE TRAILER DUE TO THE INTENSITY OF THE FIRE. *******  BY THE TIME THE FIRE DEPARTMENT ARRIVED ON THE SCENE, THE TRACTOR TRAILER WERE BOTH ENGULFED IN FLAMES AND TRACTOR, TRAILER AND CONTENTS WERE A TOTAL LOSS. INTERMODAL ROOL-OFF CONTAINER NONU26272 NOTED BY CARRIER PERSONNEL WITH LIQUID LEAKING FROM AROUND THE REAR DOR.  CONTAINER ISOLATED AND SHIPPER AND CONSIGNEE NOTIFIED.  SHIPPER REPRESENTATIVE, HERITAGE ENVIRONMENTAL, RESPONDED AND FOUND ABOVE CONTAINER DRIPPING WATER FROM THE BOTTOM CORNER OF THE CONTAINER DOOR.  CONSIGNEE REPRESENTATIVE, CHUCK OVERMAN, ADVISED THE MATERIAL INSIDE THE CONTAINERS WAS A RESIDUE SLAG FROM THE BATTERY RECYCLING PROCESS.  THE MATERIAL IS COOLED WITH WATER BEFORE SHIPMENT AND THE LIQUID WAS WATER LEAKING FROM THE SOLID MATERIAL.  A SMALL AMOUNT OF SOLID MATERIAL HAD ESCAPED WITH THE LEACHATE AND WAS CONTAINED ON THE RAIL FLATCAR.  MATERIAL ESCAPED BECAUSE THE REAR DOOR WAS NOT SECURELY TIGHTENED AFTER LOADING.  THE DOOR WAS PROPERLY SECURED, SPILLED MATERIAL COLLECTED, AND THE CONTAINER WAS FORWARDED.

A VAN TRAILER CONTAINING HAZARDOUS WASTE WAS ENROUTE FROM XEROX LOCATED AT P O BOX 2000 IN LEESBURG, VA TO CLEAN HARBORS SERVICES, INC. LOCATED AT 11800 SOUTH STONEY ISLAND AVENUE IN CHICAGO, IL.  DURING A ROUTINE STOP AT CLEAN HARBORS OF BALTIMORE, INC. LOCATED AT 1910 RUSSELL STREET IN BALTIMORE, MD IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT APPROXIMATELY 1 GALLON HAD ESCAPED FROM A PINHOLE LEAK THAT HAD DEVELOPED ON THE BOTTOM OF ONE OF THE CONTAINERS ONTO THE FLOOR OF THE VAN TRAILER WHERE IT WAS PREVENTED FROM ESCAPING TO THE ENVIRONMENT.  FACILITY PERSONNEL IMMEDIATELY CONTAINED THE RELEASE, ABSORBED ALL FREE LIQUIDS WITH SPEEDI DRY AND PLACED THE DAMAGED CONTAINER INTO A SUITABLE SALVAGE DRUM.  ALL CLEAN UP DEBRIS GENERATED AS A RESULT OF THE RELEASE WAS PLACED INTO THE SALVAGE DRUM AND WAS DISPOSED OF AT THE WASTE MANAGEMENT FACILITY INDICATED ON THE ORIGINAL SHIPPING DOCUMENT.   PRIOR TO DEPARTURE FROM THE SHIPPER'S LOCATION, ALL CONTAINERS WERE INSPECTED AND NO EVIDENCE OF LEAKING WAS OBSERVED.  DRIVERS WILL CONTINUE TO INSPECT EACH CONTAINER AS IT IS LOADED AND WILL CONTINUE TO TAKE APPROPRIATE ACTIONS IN THE EVENT A CONTAINER IS FOUND TO BE LEAKING OR DAMAGED.

A VAN TRAILER CONTAINING BOTH HAZARDOUS WASTE AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS WAS ENROUTE FROM CLEAN HARBORS OF BRAINTREE, INC. LOCATED AT 385 QUINCY AVENUE IN BRAINTREE, MA TO CLEAN HARBORS TECHNOLOGY CORP. LOCATED 5 MILES SOUTH, RT 71 IN KIMBALL, NE.  DURING THE COURSE OF THE TRIP, THE DRIVER MADE A ROUTINE MEAL AND REST STOP AT THE IOWA 80 TRUCK STOP LOCATED AT EXIT 284 ON IOWA 80 WEST.  DURING THIS STOP, THE DRIVER WAS NOTIFIED BY THE MANAGEMENT OF THE TRUCK STOP THAT A SMALL AMOUNT OF MATERIAL WAS OBSERVED LEAKING FROM THE CARGO CARRYING PORTION OF HIS VEHICLE AND THAT THE WALCOTT FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS CALLED TO THE SCENE.  IN ADDITION, THE DAVENPORT IA HAZARDOUS MATERIALS RESPONSE TEAM WAS CALLED TO THE SCENE TO IDENTIFY THE SOURCE AND IDENTITY OF THE MATERIAL BEING RELEASED.  UPON ARRIVAL TO THE SCENE, THE EMERGENCY RESPONDERS ESTABLISHED A 50 FOOT EXCLUSION ZONE AROUND THE VEHICLE AND SPREAD ABSORBENT MATERIAL AROUND THE VEHICLE TO CONTAIN THE MATERIAL THAT HAD ESCAPED FROM THE TRAILER.  WHILE THIS WAS BEING DONE, THE DRIVER OF THE VEHICLE CONTACTED HIS HOME DISPATCHER WHO IN TURN DISPATCHED A RESPONSE CREW TO THE SCENE.  MEMBERS OF THE DAVENPORT FIRE DEPARTMENT ENTERED THE TRAILER AND DISCOVERED THAT A PINHOLE LEAK HAD DEVELOPED NEAR THE BOTTOM CHIME OF ONE OF THE DRUMS ALLOWING APPROXIMATELY 1 GALLON OF TETRACHLOROETHYLENE TO ESCAPE FROM THE DRUM ONTO THE FLOOR OF THE VAN TRAILER AND THE ASPHALT PARKING AREA.  THE DECISION WAS THEN MADE BY THE FIRE DEPARTMENT TO PATCH THE LEAK PENDING THE ARRIVAL OF CLEAN HARBOR'S EMERGENCY RESPONSE CREW.  THIS WAS DONE WITHOUT INCIDENT.  AT THIS POINT, THE RESPONDING FIRE DEPARTMENTS LEFT THE SCENE AND THE DRIVER WAITED FOR THE ARRIVAL OF THE CLEAN HARBOR'S RESPONSE CREW.  UPON ARRIVAL AT THE SCENE, CLEAN HARBOR'S PERSONNEL PLACED THE DAMAGED CONTAINER INTO A SUITABLE SALVAGE DRUM.  IN ADDITION, ALL ABSORBENT MATERIAL AND CLEAN-UP DEBRIS WAS CONTAINERIZED AND TRANSPORTED TO CLEAN HARBORS TECHNOLOGY CORP. FACILITY FOR DISPOSAL.  ******* PRIOR TO DEPARTURE FROM THE SHIPPER'S LOCATION, ALL CONTAINERS WERE INSPECTED AND NO EVIDENCE OF LEAKING WAS OBSERVED.  DRIVERS WILL CONTINUE TO INSPECT EACH CONTAINER AS IT IS LOADED AND WILL CONTINUE TO TAKE APPROPRIATE ACTIONS IN THE EVENT A CONTAINER IS FOUND TO BE LEAKING OR DAMAGED.

column168: TRAILER HAD BEEN LOADED BY SHIPPER PLANT PERSONNEL, DRIVER WAS IN BREAK ROOM AS PER INSTRUCTED.  HE WAS RELEASED, AND DEPARTED PLANT. NONE COULD BE FOUND ON HIGHWAY OR ROAD LEADING FROM PLANT.  IT WAS RAINING HEAVILY, BUT THE MATERIAL IS NOT SOLUBLE IN WATER.  ALL ESCAPED MATERIAL COATED THE VEHICLE SURFACES WHERE IT LANDED.  TRAILER WAS CLEANED EXTERNALLY AT ALBANY, NY AT QUALA-SYSTEMS, INC AND ALLOWED TO PROCEED.

WHEN AIR WAS APPLIED, THE LOADER REALIZED HE HAD MADE THE PROPER CONNECTIONS & SHUT DOWN THE AIR.  WHILE ATTEMPTING TO BLEED THE EXCESS PRESSURE FROM THE CAR, HE KNOCKED THE AIR LINE'S CHICAGO FITTING LOOSE & PRODUCT FLOWED FROM THE TOP OF THE CAR UNTIL THE PRESSURE EQUALIZED.  BIDS PERSONNEL NEUTRALIZED THE SPILLED ACID WITH LIME.  THE UNLOADING CONNECTIONS WERE CHANGED & THE TANK WAS UNLOADED WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT.

column168: ON SEPTEMBER 18, SHORTLY BEFORE 2:00 A.M., A CG&E CARGO TANK TRUCK DRIVER AT CG&E'S QUEENSGATE FACILITY (424 GEST STREET) FILLED ONE OF THE TRUCK'S TWO COMPARTMENTS WITH DIESEL FUEL IN PREPARTION FOR HIS NIGHT'S RUN. THIS FUEL IS DISPENSED TO CG&E CREW TRUCKS DURING THE NIGHT SO THAT THE VEHICLES ARE READY FOR ELECTRIC AND GAS SERVICE OPERATIONS IN THE MORNING. AFTER FILLING THE CARGO TANK WITH DIESEL, THE DRIVER DEPARTED THE FACILITY FOR CG&E'S DANA AVENUE FACILITY (2004 DANA AVENUE). ALTHOUGH THE DRIVER BELIEVED HE HAD SECURED THE LATCH TO THE FILL PORT (ON TOP OF THE TANKER), THE LATCH WAS APPARENTLY LOOSE, SINCE DIESEL SPILLED FROM THE FILL PORT AS THE TRUCK PROCEEDED DOWN GEST STREET. THE SPILL CREATED ON OILY STRIPE DOWN THE PUBLIC STREET, HEAVIEST IN THE VICINITY OF GEST AND THIRD STREETS, ABOUT 40 YARDS LONG AND A COUPLE OF FEET WIDE. THE SPILL WAS CONFINED TO THE STREET SURFACE AND DID NOT IMPACT WATERWAYS, SEWERS, OR EARTH. CG&E DISCOVERED THE SPILL AT ABOUT 2:05 A.M. AND PROMPTLY DISPATCHED A CLEAN-UP CREW TO SPREAD ABSORBENT CLAY OVER OILY AREAS AND RECOVER AS MUCH OF THE SPILL OIL AS POSSIBLE. THE TRUCK DRIVER WAS CONTACTED AT DANA AVENUE AND PROMPTLY CHECKED HIS TRUCK, THEN RETRACED HIS ENTIRE ROUTE TO SEARCH FOR ANY ADDITIONAL SPILLED MATERIAL. EVALUATION OF THE CARGO TANK'S FUEL INVENTORY LED TO THE DETERMINATION THAT A MAXIMUM OF 19 GALLONS WERE SPILLED. CG&E NOTIFIED OHIO EPA, HAMILTON COUNTY, AND THE CINCINNATI FIRE DEPARTMENT CONCERNING THE INCIDENT SO AS TO ADVISE POTENTIALLY INTERESTED EMERGENCY RESPONDERS.

column168: DAVIS EXPRESS DRIVER WAS EAST BOUND ON HWY 192 BETWEEN ORLANDO, FL AND MELBOURNE, FL ENROUTE TO HIS SECOND STOP IN FT. PIERCE, FL. OUR DRIVER PASSED ANOTHER VEHICLE AND THE VEHICLE BEING PASSED NOTIFIED OUR DRIVER VIA CB RADIO THAT SOMETHING WAS LEAKING OUT OF THE BACK OF HIS TRAILER. AS IMMEDIATELY AS OUR DRIVER COULD GET OFF THE ROAD, HE PULLED OVER AND OPENED THE TRAILER DOOR. A 55 GAL. DRUM HAD TURNED OVER AND ONE OF THE PALLETS HAD PUNCTURED A HOLE IN THE SIDE OF THE DRUM. THE DRIVER STOOD THE DRUM UPRIGHT TO STOP IT FROM LEAKING. THE REASON FOR THE DRUM TURNING OVER WAS THAT IT WAS A PLASTIC DRUM LOADED ON A WOOD PALLET WHICH CAUSED IT TO SLIDE EASILY. ALSO, THERE WAS NOT ENOUGH SHRINK WRAP TO CONTAIN THE DRUMS TO PALLET. APPROXIMATELY 15 GALLONS LEAKED OUT.
VALVES WERE NOT SET PROPERLY ON PREVIOUS LOAD.  CAUSED PRODUCT TO BACK UP INTO OUT TANK AND SPILL OUT OF THE OVERFLOW.  LOST 20 GALLONS.  SPILL WAS CONTAINED AND CLEANED UP AND DISPOSED OF.

CONRAIL SPOTTED RAILCAR PLMX 4618 ON 9/25/96. ON 9/26/96, APPROXIMATELY 6:30 AM, A LAROCHE EMPLOYEE BEGAN UNLOADING PROCEDURES. THE RAILCAR ROLLED DOWN THE TRACK APPROXIMATELY 30 FEET UNDER ITS OWN POWER, WHICH SEPARATED THE TRANSFER LINE FROM THE STORAGE TANK AND CAUSED A RELEASE OF AMMONIA. IT STOPPED ON ITS OWN AGAINST A COVERED HOPPER CAR. THE LAROCHE EMPLOYEE SECURED THE RAILCAR AND CONTACTED THE FIRE DEPARTMENT IMMEDIATELY. THE RAILCARS SUSTAINED MINIMAL DAMAGE. UPON ARRIVAL OF THE FIRE DEPARTMENT, THEY BEGAN FOGGING THE AREA WITH WATER, WHICH ENABLED US TO SHUT OFF THE VALVES AT THE STORAGE TANK. TWO FACTORS CONTRIBUTED TO THE RELEASE: THE HAND BRAKE WAS NOT ENGAGED AND THE WHEEL CHOCK WERE INEFFECTIVE. CORRECTIVE MEASURES: PRIOR TO CONNECTING THE RAILCAR, AN INSPECTION MUST BE DONE TO INSURE THAT IT IS PROPERLY CHOCKED AND THE HAND BRAKE SET.

DEFECTIVE VAPOR VALVE, HCPX 1256, SEPTEMBER 26, 1996, ALBANY DIVISION AT APPROXIMATELY 0253 HOURS, SEPTEMBER 26, 1996, A CONRAIL LOCOMOTIVE ENGINEER DISCOVERED EMPTY TANK CAR HCPX 1256 LAST CONTAINING CHLORINE LEAKING FROM ONE OF THE VAPOR VALVES. A C-KIT WAS INSTALLED AND THE LEAK WAS STOPPED AT 1015 HOURS. AT APPROXIMATELY 1630 HOURS, SEPTEMBER 26, 1996, OCCIDENTAL CHEMICAL TRUCKED OFF ALL THE PRESSURE IN THE CAR TO ALLOW CAR TO MOVE TO THEIR FACILITY AND THE CAR WAS RELEASED FOR TRANSPORTATION. AT APPROXIMATELY 1100 HOURS, SEPTEMBER 27, 1996, CAR WAS DELIVERED TO OCCIDENTAL AND THEY UNLOADED THE CAR.

ON 9/23/96, SPILLAGE IS DISCOVERED WHILE UNLOADING A VAN/TRAILER AT THE LOCATION NOTED AS FOLLOWS:  ADMIRAL ROOFING, 5 LOPEZ ROAD, WILMINGTON, MA, 01887.  QUALIFIED ENTRY AND INVESTIGATION DETERMINED NO ADVERSE ENVIRONMENTAL IMPACT RESULTING FROM THIS INCIDENT.  RECOVERY OPERATIONS DETERMINED LEAKAGE LIKELY DUE TO "SHIFTING" DURING OVER-THE-ROAD TRANSPORT.  TWENTY (20) CONTAINERS DESCRIBED AS FIVE (5) GALLON PAILS ARE "OVERPACKED" IN A SINGLE "FLEX BIN" FOR SAFE RETURN TO THE SHIPPER.  NO WASTE IS GENERATED WITH RECOVERY OPERATIONS WITH PRODUCT CONFIRMED FOR "BENEFICIAL USE."  THE CAUSE OF THE LEAK CAN ONLY BE SPECULATED NOTING IT PROBABLE THAT SPACING/VOIDS BETWEEN PALLETS CREATED ROOM FOR "SHIFT" OF LOAD.  LOAD/UNLOAD PROCEDURES ARE REVIEWED WITH THE TRANSPORTER AND SHIPPER TO PREVENT FUTURE OCCURRENCE.  WE ENCLOSE COPY OF THE BILL OF LADING AND MSDS FOR YOUR PERMANENT RECORD.

DRIVER STOPPED AT WEIGH STATION AT SUSCQUAHANNA TOLL BOOTH ON 1-95 S. DURING ROUTINE DOT INSPECTION A SMALL DRIP LEAK WAS DETECTED FROM THE BOLTS ON THE FLANGE FOR THE DISCHARGE VALVE.  THE TRUCK WAS ISOLATED IN THE HOLDING AREA.  RESPONDING WERE THE PERRYVILLE VOL FIRE DEPT, HARFORD COUNTY HAZMAT TEAM, MD DEPT OF ENVIRONMENT HAZMAT TEAM AND DELTA CHEMICAL EMERGENCY COORDINATOR.  AFTER INSPECTION OF THE TANK BY THE MD DEPT OF ENVIRONMENT HAZMAT TEAM IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE RATE OF RELEASE WAS ABOUT 1 DROP EVERY 2-3 MINUTES.  THERE WAS NO STRUCTURAL DAMAGE VISIBLE. M.D.E. DETERMINED THAT IT WAS SAFE TO TRANSPORT THE TANK, UNDER ESCORT, BACK TO DELTA CHEMICAL CORP APPROX 35 MILES AFTER PACKING THE FLANGE WITH AN ABSORBENT MATERIAL.  THE TANK TRUCK RETURNED TO DELTA CHEMICAL AND OFF LOADED WITHOUT INCIDENT.  INSPECTION OF THE TANK SHOWED PITTING IN THE SUMP ABOVE THE DISCHARGE VALVE WHICH ALLOWED A SMALL QUANTITY OF ACID TO SEEP DOWN AROUND THE BOLTS.  ALL OTHER TANK TRUCKS HAULING THE SAME PRODUCT HAVE BEEN INSPECTED AND THE TANK INVOLVED HAS BEEN REPAIRED.

EXCESSIVE PRESSURE CAUSED THE HOSE TO DISCONNECT FROM THE PUMP CAUSING A SPILL OF APPROXIMATELY 50 GALLONS OF TETRACHLOROETHYLENE UNTO THE GROUND. ABSORBANT SOCKS AND PADS WERE USED TO CONTAIN AND CLEAN UP THE SPILL. THE TOP FOUR INCHES OF TOP SOIL WERE REMOVED AND PLACED INTO METAL CONTAINERS AS INSTRUCTED BY THE MISSOURI DNR. ** TO CORRECT THE PRESSURE PROBLEM, WE REGEARED THE POWER TAKE OFF DRIVE THE HYDRAULIC PUMP. THIS REDUCED THE HYDRAULIC FLOW RATE IN HALF AND LOWERED THE HYDRAULIC PRESSURE AS WELL. THIS ADJUSTMENT HAS BROUGHT PRODUCT SYSTEMS PRESSURES AND FLOW RATES DOWN TO CURRENT FLEET STANDARDS.

column168: TANK CONTAINING RESIDUAL SOLIDS WAS LOADED INTO ROLL-OFF CONTAINER FOR SHIPMENT FOR DISPOSAL AT CWM'S EMELLE. AL LANDFILL. APPARENTLY WHAT APPEARED TO BE SOLIDS AT THE BOTTOM OF THE TANK MASKED A SMALL AMOUNT OF LIQUID RESIDUE IN THE BOTTOM OF THE TANK. DURING SHIPMENT OF THE TANK, THE TANK SHIFTED AND THE FLOOR CONTACT CAUSED A CRACK IN A SMALL VALVE ON THE BOTTOM OF THE TANK WHICH ALLOWED THE SMALL AMOUNT OF LIQUID (APPX. 15 GAL) TO LEAK OUT INTO THE ROLL-OFF CONTAINER. ABOUT 11:30 A.M. THE DRIVER NOTICED A SMALL AMOUNT OF LIQUID LEAKING FROM HIS VEHICLE. HE STOPPED THE TRUCK AND ABSORBED THE SPILLED LIQUID AND SECURED THE LOAD. HE PROCEEDED ON HIS TRIP, STOPPING EVERY 30 MINUTES TO MAKE SURE THERE WERE NO FURTHER RELEASES. ** RECOMMENDATIONS: 1. THIS MATERIAL SHOULD HAVE BEEN SHIPPED WITHOUT THE "WASTE" DESIGNATION. IT IS NOT A RCRA WASTE. DRIVER HAS BEEN COUNSELLED ON THE USE OF "WASTE" ON A MANIFEST. 2. TANKS SHOULD BE CHECKED MORE THOROUGHLY FOR LIQUID RESIDUE, ABSORBENT SHOULD BE ADDED AS A PRECAUTION, AND VALVE INTEGRITY SHOULD BE CHECKED PRIOR TO SHIPMENTS. PROPER LOADING OF INNER CONTAINERS WILL BE VERIFIED PRIOR TO LEAVING SITE.

POLICE ALSO STATED THEY HAVE HAD OTHER PROBLEMS OF AUTO'S PLAYING CHICKEN WITH ONCOMING TRAFFIC IN THAT AREA.  THERE IS A WITNESS THAT CONFIRMS THIS INCIDENT.  THE DRIVER SEEN THE ONCOMING CAR HEADED TOWARD HIM, HE SLOWED DOWN AND WENT OVER TO THE RIGHT AS FAR AS POSSIBLE TO AVOID THE CAR.  SOFT GROUND TOOK THE RIG INTO THE DITCH AND THE UNIT LEANED ON IT'S SIDE.  THE LIQUID ROAD PAVING ASPHALT THAT THE TRUCK WAS CARRYING APPROXIMATELY 5,000 GALS.,  2000 GALS WAS SPILLED, THE REMAINING 3,000 GALS.  WAS PUMPED OFF BY ANOTHER TRUCK AND WAS TAKEN  TO CONSIGNEE. ALL PROPER AUTHORITIES WERE AT THE SCENE.  PLEASE NOTE ONCE THE ROAD PAVING ASPHALT WAS EXPOSED AND ON THE GROUND,  IT IMMEDIATELY LOST ITS ELEVATED TEMPERATURE AND WAS NO LONGER CONSIDERED A HAZARD.

column62: Abrasion; Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: ON SATURDAY SEPTEMBER 21ST AT APPROXIMATELY 03:45 HOURS, DRIVER JOHN MCCUNE WAS SOUTHBOUND ON 135 JUST NORTH OF THE STORY CITY EXIT. HE WAS DRIVING A SEMI TANKER OWNED BY TRANSWOOD, INC. DRIVER LOST CONTROL OF HIS SEMI AND ROLLED THE TANKER ON THE TRAVELED PORTION OF THE INTERSTATE. DRIVER HAD MINOR INJURIES AND WAS LATER TAKEN TO MGMC IN AMES WHERE HE WAS TREATED AND RELEASED. THE TANKER CONTAINED APPROXIMATELY 6,000 GALLONS OF MEK/TOLUENE COMPOUND. THIS MATERIAL IS VERY FLAMMABLE. STORY CITY FIRE VOLUNTEER DEPARTMENT RESPONDED AND ESTABLISHED INCIDENT COMMAND. LAW ENFORCEMENT SECURED THE AREA 1000 FEET AROUND THE ACCIDENT. TRAFFIC WAS RE-ROUTED AND THE INTERSTATE WAS CLOSED FROM THE RANDALL EXIT TO THE STORY CITY EXIT. DES MOINES HAZMAT AND NUMEROUS AGENCIES WERE CALLED IN TO ASSIST WITH THE INCIDENT. EVENTUALLY, THE REMAINING PRODUCT WAS OFF LOADED. IT WAS DETERMINED THAT APPROXIMATELY 3,000 GALLONS WERE RELEASED INTO ROADWAY AND INTO THE WEST DITCH. THE POOLED PRODUCT WAS PUMPED OUT OF THE DITCH AND TRANSWOOD HIRED SENECA ENVIRONMENTAL TO HANDLE THE CLEANUP. ONE MAJOR CONCERN TO THIS INCIDENT WAS THE EXCESSIVE TRAFFIC COMING FROM WATERLOO EN ROUTE TO AMES FOR THE UNI/ISU FOOTBALL GAME. THE NORTHBOUND LANE WAS OPENED UP AT APPROXIMATELY 12:02 HOURS. THE ENTIRE SB LANE WAS OPENED UP AT APPROXIMATELY 1300 HRS. THE COMPANY HAS BEEN CONTACTED REGARDING THE COST RECOVERY. 3 CITATIONS WERE ISSUED. APPROXIMATELY 22 AGENCIES AND BUSINESSES WERE INVOLVED IN THE RESPONSE & RECOVERY OF THIS INCIDENT. THE INTERSTATE WAS AT LEAST PARTIALLY CLOSED DOWN FOR 12 HOURS.

GATX RAILCAR BEING LOADED AT FINA PAR RAILCAR LOADING RACK WAS INADVERTENTLY OVERFILLED. LOADING OPERATION WAS STOPPED & SECURED. ABSORBENT BOOM AND PADS WERE USED TO CONTAIN THE SPILL. NEARBY DRAINAGE DITCH WAS SECURED WITH PLYWOOD AND EARTHEN DAM. SODA ASH WAS USED TO NEUTRALIZE SPENT SULFURIC ACID SPILL. SOIL PH WAS TESTED AND DETERMINED TO BE WITHIN 7 RANGE. FINA PAR CONTRACTED TRIANGLE INDUSTRIAL SERVICE, INC. TO  CONTAIN, RECOVER AND CLEAN-UP THE SPENT SULFURIC ACID SPILL. VACUUM TRUCKS WERE USED TO RECOVER DITCH WATER AND TRANSPORT TO FINA PAR'S ON-SITE PWTC (PROCESS WATER TREATMENT COMPLEX) FOR TREATMENT. THE DITCH AND SOIL WERE FLUSHED WITH WATER UNTIL PH WAS WITHIN A NEUTRAL 7 RANGE (7.2 TO 7.8). SODA ASH WAS ADDED AS NECESSARY TO DITCH WATER TO AID IN THE NEUTRALIZATION. SODA ASH WAS MIXED IN WITH SHOVELS ON ALL AFFECTED SOIL AREA. SPILL WAS CONTAINED WITHIN IMMEDIATE AREA RAILCAR LOADING RACK WITH FINA PAR FACILITY. NO OFF-SITE IMPACT OF ANY KIND OCCURRED (ENVIRONMENTAL OR GENERAL PUBLIC). RAILCAR LOADING PROCEDURES WERE REVIEWED WITH OPERATORS RESPONSIBLE FOR OPERATING RAILCAR ACID LOADING RACK. TOTAL ESTIMATED SPILL WAS 5 BARRELS (220 GALLONS) APPROXIMATELY.

TOP VALVE ON TOTE CAME LOOSE, CAUSING LIQUID TO SPILL IN TRAILER. CONTENTS OF SPILL CONTAINED IN TRAILER. SPILL CLEANED UP WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL, PUT IN DRUM AND DISPOSED OF BY LAIDLAW ENVIRONMENTAL.

column168: MATERIAL HANDLER SPOTTED THE TRUCK AND PREPARED TO LOAD. TRUCK WAS ISOLATED AND ROADWAY CLOSED OFF. THE MATERIAL HANDLER AND PHENOL UNIT OPERATOR WERE STATIONED AT THE LOADING PUMP AREA BY THE PUMP SHUTOFF VALVE. DUE TO THE NATURE OF THE PRODUCT THE PROCEDURE IS TO PLACE ANYONE ON THE LOADING RACK DURING THE LOADING PROCESS. THE OUTLET AND LOADING MANWAY ARE MONITORED ON THE GROUND BY THE TRUCK DRIVER WHO WAS PROVIDED A RADIO FOR IMMEDIATE COMMUNICATION TO THE MATERIAL HANDLERS SHOULD ANY PROBLEM ARISE. THE AMOUNT LOADED IN THE TANKER IS MEASURED BY A LOADING METER LOCATED AT THE LOADING PUMP AND IS CONSTANTLY MONITORED EVEN THOUGH IT HAS AN AUTOMATIC SHUT-OFF. JUST AS THE MATERIAL HANDLER STARTED TO THROTTLE THE PUMP DISCHARGE - THE DRIVER CALLED THAT THE TANKER WAS STARTING TO OVERFLOW. FLOW WAS STOPPED IMMEDIATELY. EMERGENCY NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE. 90% OF THE MATERIAL WAS RECOVERED AND REPROCESSED. LESS THAN 1 GALLON WAS LOST. THERE WERE NO INJURIES. DRIVERS DID NOT NOTIFY THEIR MANAGEMENT AT THE CARRIER SINCE THEY BELIEVED THAT ARISTECH HAD MADE ALL NECESSARY NOTIFICATIONS.

1N THURSDAY, SEPTEMBER 12, 1996, AT APPROXIMATELY 7:00 A.M. CARL BENNETT, MESQUITE DRIVER, WAS DRIVING HIS TRACTOR-TRAILER, APPROXIMATELY 35 MILES PER HOUR, WEST ON I-635, IN THE RIGHT LANE, PREPARING TO EXIT AT MIDWAY ROAD. JUST PRIOR TO MIDWAY ROAD THE DALLAS NORTH TOLLWAY ENTERS I-635. THERE IS A LONG ENTRANCE RAMP WITH A WIDE BUTTONED OFF AREA DIVIDING THE RAMP FROM I-635. A CAR DROVE ACROSS THIS BUTTONED OFF AREA RIGHT IN FRONT OF CARL INTO THE SECOND LANE OVER. CARL HAD TO SLAM ON HIS BRAKES IN ORDER TO KEEP FROM HITTING THE CAR. HE FELT HIS LOAD SHIFT. ** AS HE CONTINUED TOWARD MIDWAY ROAD, HE MOVED INTO THE FAR RIGHT HAND LANE PRIOR TO THE ACTUAL EXIT RAMP. HE LOOKED OUT OF HIS REAR VIEW MIRROR AND SAW LIQUID POURING FROM THE LEFT SIDE OF HIS TRAILER. WHERE HE WAS AT THAT TIME, THE ROAD TILTS BACK TOWARD I-635 SO CARL QUICKLY MOVED FURTHER TOWARD THE SIDE OF THE ROAD WERE IT TILTED OFF THE ROAD INSTEAD OF TOWARD I-635. HE PULLED OFF THE ROAD AND STOPPED. ** HE WENT TO THE RIGHT OF HIS TRAILER AND CAREFULLY OPENED THE SIDE DOOR. MORE OF THE SPILLED PRODUCT RAN OUT THE DOOR. THE SPILLED PRODUCT APPEARED TO BE ACID, BUT HE COULD NOT SEE WHAT WAS LEAKING. HE OPENED THE BACK DOORS BUT STILL COULD NOT SEE WHAT WAS LEAKING, BUT HE COULD SEE IT WAS NOT THE TOTES. HE WENT BACK TO THE CAB OF HIS TRUCK TO CALL THE OPERATION MANAGER, DON DIXON, AND CHECK THE SHIPPING PAPERS FOR WHAT THE PRODUCT MIGHT BE. FROM LOOKING AT THE SHIPPING PAPERS HE DEDUCTED THAT THE SPILLED PRODUCT WAS PROBABLY MAYOQUEST 1500--CORROSIVE LIQUID, N.O.S. (1-HYDROXYETHYLIDENE-1, 1-DIPHOSPHONIC ACID), 8, CORROSIVE, UN1760, PG111. HE CALLED DON AND TOLD HIM THAT HE THOUGHT THE SPILLED PRODUCT WAS MAYOQUEST 1500. DON HAD A. ABDULLAH, ANOTHER MESQUITE DRIVER, DRIVE A BOB-TAIL WITH ANOTHER PALLET JACK TO THE SCENE. DON AND LEON PAGE, DIRECTOR, DROVE TO THE SCENE IN DON'S VAN. ** SOMEONE ELSE MUST HAVE CALLED 911 BECAUSE THE FIRE DEPARTMENT SHOWED UP WHILE CARL WAS ON THE PHONE. IT WAS APPROXIMATELY 7:05 TO 7:10 A.M. CARL AND THE FIREMAN CRAWLED INTO THE BACK OF THE TRAILER. A TOTE HAD PRESSED UP AGAINST A SINGLE 55 GALLON DRUM AT MAYOQUEST 1500 AND SPLIT THE DRUM. THE ENTIRE 55 GALLONS HAD LEAKED FROM THE DRUM. ** FRED CHANDLER, VICE PRESIDENT, DROVE BY THE SCENE JUST AFTER IT HAD HAPPENED. WHILE HE LOOPED AROUND AT THE NEXT EXIT TO GET BACK TO THE SCENE, HE CALLED THE OFFICE AND FOUND OUT WHAT THE SPILLED PRODUCT WAS. HE THEN CALLED CALLAWAY, A DIVISION OF VULCAN CHEMICAL, THE MANUFACTURER OF MAYOQUEST. HE GOT THEIR TECHNICAL MAN, STEVE REDDING, ON HIS MOBILE PHONE WHEN HE GOT TO THE SCENE. HE GAVE THE PHONE (AND ALSO HIS EMERGENCY RESPONSE BOOK) TO THE FIREMAN IN CHARGE WHO QUESTION THE CALLAWAY TECHNICAL MAN ABOUT THE PRODUCT AND WHAT TO DO TO SAFELY CLEAN IT UP. ** IN THE MEAN TIME, THE POLICE HAD ARRIVED, BLOCKED OFF TWO LANES OF I-635 PLUS THE EXIT RAMP TO MIDWAY ROAD, AND WERE QUESTIONING CARL. THE POLICEMAN CHECKED ALL DOT REQUIREMENTS ON THE TRUCK. EVERYTHING WAS OKAY EXC

RESPONDED TO THE SPILL. PROCESSED VIA THE DMP PROGRAM. FOLLOWED THE DECISION TREE. LOOSE CAP CAUSED LEAKAGE. PLACED IN BAG FOLLOWING UPS DISPOSAL PROCEDURES. I WORE THE PROPER P.P.E. FOLLOWED THE RESPONSE SHEET GUIDELINES. BUS DEVL A.E. TO FOLLOW - UP WITH THE SHIPPER. SOLIDIFIED/PROCESSED WITH SODIUM BICARBONATE.

THE SPILL WAS CLEANED AND NEUTRALIZED AND THE CARGO BIN WAS INSPECTED BY AN AIRCRAFT MECHANIC. OTHER BAGGAGE AND MAIL WAS DAMAGED BY THE FLUID FOR THE BATTERIES WHICH WERE ALSO CLEANED AND DECONTAMINATED AND RELOADED FOR SHIPMENT TO THEIR FINAL DESTINATION.

column168: NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER REFERENCE # 362433 NEW YORK STATE DEPT. OF ENVIRONMENTAL CONSERVATION REFERENCE # 96-07976 OUR DRIVER WAS OPERATING A 1987 MACK TRACTOR PULLING A 1993 FRUEHAUF CARGO TANK ON HIS FIRST DELIVERY OF THE DAY.  HE HAD LOADED 8,003 GALLONS OF REFORMULATED GASOLINE FOR THE GIBBS OIL CO STATION IN NORTH ADAMS, MASSACHUSETTS.  IN THE VILLAGE OF NEW LEBANON, NY, OUR DRIVER HAD TO MAKE A LEFT TURN ONTO STATE RT 22 NORTH. IN THE PROCESS OF MAKING THIS LEFT TURN, OUR DRIVER STATES THAT HE SWERVED TO AVOID DEER IN THE ROAD.  IN THE PROCESS, HE OVERTURNED THE VEHICLE ONTO ITS RIGHT SIDE.  OUR DRIVER WAS ABLE TO ESCAPE OUT A WINDOW.  THE VEHICLE IMMEDIATELY CAUGHT FIRE AND WAS DESTROYED.  SOME GASOLINE FLOWED ONTO A GRASSY AREA AND INTO A NEARBY DITCH WHERE IT WAS CONTAINED.  THERE WAS EXTENSIVE HEAT DAMAGED TO A NEARBY SERVICE STATION, SEVERAL POWER LINES, & POLES AS WELL AS MINOR DAMAGE TO A CAR PARKED IN THE AREA.  OUR DRIVER RECEIVED MINOR CUTS.  HE WAS NOT HOSPITALIZED BUT CONTINUES TO RECEIVE TREATMENT FOR CHEMICAL BRONCHITIS CAUSED BY THE EXPOSURE TO THE GASOLINE FUMES.  PLEASE NOTE THAT DAMAGE AMOUNTS ARE ESTIMATES ONLY.

column168: DURING THE FLIGHT THE BOX IN QUESTION BEGAN EMITTING A STRONG GASOLINE-LIKE ODOR.  THE PILOT RETURNED THE AIRCRAFT TO THE LAS VEGAS INTERNATIONAL AIRPORT.  THE AIRCRAFT WAS DOWNLOADED AND THIS PACKAGE WAS FOUND TO BE GIVING OFF THE GASOLINE ODOR.  SINCE THERE WAS AN IN-AIR DIVERSION I NOTIFIED THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER.  I SPOKE TO A MAN NAMED CHEN AND ADVISED HIM OF THE NATURE OF MY CALL.  THE REPORT NUMBER HE GAVE ME WAS 362873 CHEN.  THE PACKAGE WAS REMOVED FROM THE AIRCRAFT AND PLACED IN THE DANGEROUS GOODS HOLDING AREA.  I CALLED THE FAA CASFU IN LAS VEGAS, REPORTED THE INCIDENT AND WAS TOLD BY THE LADY THAT ANSWERED THE PHONE THAT SHE WOULD PASS THE INFO ALONG TO A CASE AGENT.  THE SHIPPER HAS BEEN NOTIFIED.  WE WILL HOLD THE FREIGHT PENDING AN FAA INSPECTION AND RELEASE. ONCE THAT IS ACCOMPLISHED THE SHIPPER WILL BE RENOTIFIED FOR SHIPPING PAPERS.

column168: DEAN C COOPER, MGR, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS CONTACTED BY ROBERT SPINKS, SPECIAL AGENT, HAZARDOUS MATERIAL.  HE ADVISED THAT SUPERVISOR, YARD OPERATIONS, YERMO, CA HAD REPORTED A TANK CAR LEAKING FROM THE TOP DURING NORMAL SWITCHING OPERATIONS.  THE TANK CAR WAS SET TO THE CABOOSE TRACK AND ISOLATED PENDING AN INSPECTION.  AS SPECIAL AGENT SPINKS WAS IN LAS VEGAS AT THE TIME, HE DROVE TO THE YERMO YARD FACILITY, INSPECTED THE CAR, AND FOUND THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK TO BE FROM A BURST FRANGIBLE DISC IN THE SAFETY VENT.  THE SAFETY VENT, A STANDARD GATX 3 BOLT COATED FLANGE ASSEMBLY MOUNTED ADJACENT TO THE MANWAY, AND OUTSIDE THE WORK PLATFORM AREA, WAS DISASSEMBLED AND THE BURST DISC REPLACED WITH A LIKE TYPE 100 POUND BS&B STAINLESS/TEFLON FRANGIBLE DISC.  THE SAFETY VENT WAS REASSEMBLED, AND THE REMAINING VALVES AND FITTINGS INSPECTED, WHICH WERE FOUND TO BE PROPERLY SECURED.  SODIUM BICARBONATE WAS USED TO NEUTRALIZE THE AFFECTED AREA OF THE CAR AROUND THE SAFETY VENT.  THE CAR WAS THEN RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT ON TO THE CONSIGNEE.  DUE TO THE MINIMAL AMOUNT AND TYPE OF PRODUCT RELEASED, NOTIFICATIONS WERE ONLY MADE TO CHEMTREC FOR REPORTING PURPOSES; AND THE SHIPPER AS INFORMATION.

column168: MEMPHIS CAR FOREMAN G LOFTIN WAS INFORMED AT 1430 HRS, TUESDAY, SEPT. 24TH, BY CARMEN THAT TANK CAR CELX 2321 LOCATED IN TRACK NO. 1 WAS LEAKING AND HAD A STRONG ODOR.  AREA WAS EVACUATED.  MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY C HILL WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED.  INSPECTION OF CAR REVEALED FOUR 1/2 INCH BOLTS USED TO SECURE LIQUID VALVE TO FLANGE HAD THREE LOOSE, ONE OF WHICH WAS STRIPPED.  STRIPPED BOLT WAS REPLACED AND ALL SECURED WRENCH TIGHT, WHICH STOPPED THE LEAK.  CHEMTREC'S JOE DEBMAN WAS NOTIFIED AND ASSIGNED REPORT NO. 48090, SHIPPER REPRESENTATIVE ALFOSE WALKER WAS NOTIFIED.  TWO CARMEN, WHO WERE WITHIN 75 YARDS OF CAR, WERE TAKEN TO A LOCAL HOSPITAL FOR OBSERVATION AND RELEASED.

column58: Auxiliary Valve; Bottom Outlet Valve; Piping or Fittings
column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Defective Component or Device
column168: MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, D A LOW, WAS CONTACTED BY CHEYENNE YARD MASTER, THAT 759 SWITCH CREW NOTED TANK CAR GATX 36042 LEAKING AND HAD CAR ISOLATED ON EAST END OF SOUTH TWO TRACK, CHEYENNE YARDS.  INSPECTION REVEALED THAT PRODUCT WAS LEAKING FROM BOTTOM OUTLET ABOUT 1 PINT PER MINUTE.  TOOK ONE COMPLETE TURN ON TOP OPERATED, BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE WHICH STOPPED LEAK.  ALSO, NOTED STUFFING BOX PACKING GLAND TO BE LESS THAN TOOL TIGHT.  IT SHOULD BE NOTED THAT BOTTOM OUTLET CAP WAS FROZEN TIGHT AND WAS UNABLE TO REMOVE OR TIGHTEN.  KEN IKEBUSH, COASTAL CHEM, WAS NOTIFIED OF EXCEPTION.  MR. IKEBUSH ADVISED THAT WICKLAND OIL TERMINALS COULD NOT UNLOAD CAR, ACCOUNT OF BOTTOM OUTLET CAP, AT WHICH TIME THE CAR WAS BILLED BACK TO COASTAL CHEM.  INTACT SEAL: UP-305209, WAS REMOVED FROM TOP OPERATED, BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE, SO REPAIRS COULD BE MADE.

MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, D A LOW, DURING COMPLIANCE INSPECTION OF OGCY-28, SOUTH 4 TRACK, CHEYENNE YARDS, NOTED PRODUCT COMING FROM BETWEEN SAFETY VENT NOZZLE AND SAFETY VENT ASSEMBLY.  REMOVED SAFETY VENT ASSEMBLY, WHICH WAS LESS THAN TOOL TIGHT.  CLEANED THREADS, TAPED, AND PROPERLY SECURED VENT ASSEMBLY, WHICH STOPPED LEAK.  JEFF BOTWINICK, CHEMTREC FILE #48221 AND MONTE JOHNSTON, AGRIUM US, WERE NOTIFIED OF EXCEPTIONS.

MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, D A LOW, WAS CONTACTED BY UPRR CORRIDOR MANAGER, THAT TRAIN PCNP 28, EXTRA CNW7034, EAST, HAD DERAILED 21 CARS, MP534.5, WEST OF BULFORD, WY.  TWO TANK CARS OF PHOSPHORIC ACID WERE INVOLVED.  CREW HAD REPORTED THAT ONE TANK CAR WAS LEAKING ITS CONTENTS. INSPECTION REVEALED THAT TANK CAR GATX 13580, HAD TURNED OVER AND HAD PANCAKED AGAINST TANK CAR JRSX 1037, ALSO LOADED WITH PHOSPHORIC ACID. JRSX 1037, WAS UPRIGHT, BUT PANCAKED.  BOTH TANK CARS WERE FACING NORTH TO SOUTH AND LOCATED WITHIN AN 18 FOOT HIGH GRANITE CUT.  FURTHER INSPECTION REVEALED THAT ONLY TANK CAR LEAKING GATX 13580.  IT HAD ONE MANWAY SWING BOLT DAMAGED, WITH SMALL LEAK COMING FROM MANWAY.  FRANGIBLE DISC WAS NOT RUPTURED.  SIDE BOLSTER OF TANK CAR JRSX 1037 HAD PUNCTURED THE RIGHT SIDE OF SHELL 'A' END OF TANK CAR GATX 13580, WHICH LEFT A 2 X 3 FOOT HOLE. SECURED MANWAY LEAK AND PLACED A PLASTIC SWIMMING POOL UNDER SHELL HOLE LEAK.  GATX 13580 CONTENTS WERE TRANSFERRED INTO TANK CAR GATX 69242. JRSX 1037 CONTENTS WERE TRANSFERRED INTO TANK CAR JRSX 1038.  JIM COOPER, CHEMTREC, NORM SELF AND JEFF ROSLER, J. R. SIMPLOT, WERE NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT.

column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Defective Component or Device
column168: MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, D A LOW, DURING COMPLIANCE INSPECTION NOTED STRONG ODOR OF MTBE COMING FROM TANK CAR GATX 18592, SOUTH 3 TRACK, CHEYENNE YARDS.  INSPECTION REVEALED THAT TOP OPERATED, BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE HAD OPERATING VALVE ROD BROKEN, WITH ROD END EXTENDING ONLY THROUGH TOP EDGE OF THE PACKING GLAND.  PACKING GLAND NUT WAS 4 TURNS LOOSE.  ALSO, ONE INCH AIR CONNECTION VALVE WAS OPEN WITH PIPE PLUG LESS THAN TOOL TIGHT.  TIGHTEN PACKING GLAND AND PLUGGED.  SECURED ONE INCH AIR CONNECTION VALVE AND PLUG, WHICH STOPPED LEAKS.  LARRY HOSLER, WICKLAND OIL TERMINAL AND KEN EICKBUSH, COASTAL CHEM, WERE NOTIFIED OF EXCEPTIONS.

WHILE CONDUCTING REGULATORY COMPLIANCE INSPECTIONS AT OGDEN UT.  MGR HW RODABOUGH NOTED TANKCAR GATX 49089 WITH PRODUCT RUNNING DOWN THE SIDE OF THE CAR.  INSPECTION REVEALED, BROKEN FRANGIBLE DISC, MGR RODABOUGH REPLACED THE DISC WITH A BS&B 100# DISC IN SAFETY VENT LOCATED ON THE MANWAY COVER, THEN WASHED THE CAR WITH A SOLUTION OF SODIUM BICARBONATE AND WATER AND RELEASED THE CAR.  CHEMTREC, MRS TRACY JACKSON, FURNISHED WITH DETAILS AND ASSIGNED CASE NUMBER 47426.  THE SHIPPER RHONE POULENC ALSO ADVISED OF FINDINGS.

AT 0830 HRS ON TUESDAY THE 3RD DAY OF SEPTEMBER, MGR RODABOUGH WAS NOTIFIED BY MR CRAIG JENSEN THE M.T.O. AT OGDEN UTAH THAT TANK CAR RPBX 23206 HAS BEEN REPORTED LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM OF THE CAR.  INSPECTION BY MGR RODABOUGH REVEALED LOOSE CAP ON THE 2" EDUCTION PIPE WITH PRODUCT RUNNING OUT AND DOWN THE RIGHT SIDE OF THE CAR.  CAR HAD PRESSURE ON IT DUE TO THE HIGH AMBIENT TEMPERATURE.  MGR RODABOUGH RELEASED THE PRESSURE THROUGH THE MANWAY COVER.  HE REMOVED THE CAP AND APPLIED TEFLON TAPE TO THE THREADS, THEN RESECURED THE CAP.  THE CAR WAS WASHED DOWN WITH SOLUTION OF SODIUM BICARBONATE AND WATER, THEN RELEASED TO CONTINUE TO DESTINATION.  CHEMTREC, MRS TRACY JACKSON, FURNISHED WITH DETAILS AND ASSIGNED CASE #47426.  MR BILL HUBBS, MGR EMERGENCY RESPONSE FOR RHONE POULENC ALSO NOTIFIED OF FINDINGS.

AT 1830 HRS ON TUESDAY THE 3RD DAY OF SEPTEMBER, MGR H W RODABOUGH WAS NOTIFIED THAT CREW HAD SET OUT TANK CAR ARIX 3003 ON TRACK #9 AT MILFORD, UTAH.  CAR WAS REPORTED TO BE LEAKING FROM SIDE CONTROL BOX, VAPOR ONLY. AT 0930 HRS ON WEDNESDAY THE 4TH OF SEPTEMBER, MGR H W RODABOUGH INSPECTED TANKCAR ARIX 3003 AND FOUND THE PRESSURE RELIEF REGULATOR TO BE FROZEN IN OPEN POSITION ALLOWING SLIGHT VAPOR RELEASE.  MGR RODABOUGH CLOSED THE RELIEF REGULATOR SHUT OFF VALVE, ALLOWING THE FROZEN PIPES AND VALVES TO THAW OUT.  HE THEN RELEASED CAR PRESSURE FROM 29 PSI TO 15 PSI, THROUGH BOTH VAPOR RELIEF VALVES.  HE THEN SECURED THE CAR AND RELEASED IT TO CONTINUE TO DESTINATION.  CHEMTREC, MR CHRIS YOUNG, FURNISHED WITH DETAILS AND ASSIGNED CASE NUMBER 47510.  BOC GASES, CITY OF INDUSTRY, CA, MR. JIM SIZEMORE, ADVISED OF FINDINGS.

SPECIAL AGENT HAZARDOUS MATERIALS BALLANCE WAS ADVISED BY STOCKTON YARDMASTER THAT TANK CAR GATX 47374 WAS LEAKING FROM THE TOP OF THE CAR. SAHM BALLANCE FOUND THAT THE RUPTURE DISK ON THE CAR HAD BLOWN.  A BS&B 100# DISC WAS REMOVED AND WAS REPLACED WITH LIKE KIND.  THE OUTSIDE OF THE TANKCAR WAS CLEANED AND THE CAR WAS RELEASED TO CONTINUE ON TO DESTINATION.

REGIONAL MANAGER R M STINE WAS NOTIFIED BY MYO THAT CARMEN WORKING TRAIN NPKC-04 NOTED PRODUCT LEAKING FROM THE HEATER COIL ON CAR GATX 16964. INSPECTION DEVELOPED THE LEAK WAS A SMALL STREAM COMING FROM THE "B" END INLET TWO INCH PIPE.  ALL FOUR HEATER COIL CAPS HAD NOT BEEN APPLIED AND WERE HANGING FROM THEIR SAFETY CHAINS.  APPLIED CAPS WHICH SECURED LEAK. ALSO NOTED EVIDENCE OF PRODUCT HAVING SPLASHED FROM THE MANWAY NOZZLE AND FOUND CAR EQUIPPED WITH SIX MANWAY SWING BOLTS OF WHICH THREE WERE WRENCH TIGHT, ONE UP IN POSITION NOT TIGHT, AND TWO HANGING DOWN.  WHEN "CHEMTREC" JEFF BOTWINICK WAS CONTACTED DEVELOPED EDGINGTON OIL WAS NOT REGISTERED WITH THEIR AGENCY HOWEVER CONTACT WAS MADE AT 310-423-1465. REPORT # 47499 WAS ASSIGNED TO THE INFORMATION FURNISHED.  DUE TO THE FACT CAR HAS A FAILED INTERNAL HEATER COIL PRODUCT TRANSFER WAS REQUIRED WITH THE CONSIGNEE SUPPLYING THE RESIDUE CAR.  SEPTEMBER 16, 1996, HAZMAT RESPONSE WAS CONTRACTED TO TRANSFER THE PRODUCT FROM GATX 16964 TO GATX 93699.  THEY ARRIVED ON SITE AT 1300 HOURS AND DEPARTED AT 1730 HOURS. INTACT SEALS "SAH 009266 AND SAH 009267" WERE REMOVED FROM GATX 16964. AFTER TRANSFER WAS COMPLETE SEALS UP K 392544 AND UP K 392545 WERE APPLIED TO GATX 93699.  CAR WAS THEN BILLED TO DESTINATION.

MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, D A LOW, WAS ADVISED BY THE CORRIDOR MANAGER, THAT EASTBOUND TRAIN NOTED TANK CAR ASTX 5084, SULFURIC ACID, SPRAYING FROM TOP AREA, 11TH HEAD CAR IN TRAIN NPPC-05, WESTBOUND, MP578.50.  TRAIN WAS STOPPED AT LOOKOUT, WY, MP593.50.  INSPECTION REVEALED THAT EDUCTION PIPE TREADS WERE DAMAGED AND INTERIOR OF PIPE WAS CRACKED.  REDUCED PRESSURE WHICH STOPPED LEAK.  SINCE MGR LOW COULD NOT REPAIR THE EDUCTION PIPE, HE HAD THE CAR ISOLATED ON HOUSE TRACK AT LOOKOUT, WY.  RISKCAR INC ARRIVED AT LOOKOUT AT 1430 HRS 09/06/96 AND CUT OFF OLD EDUCTION PIPE, WELDED NEW PIPE TO EDUCTION FLANGE, AND APPLIED NEW PIPE CAP, WHICH PROPERLY SECURED THE LEAK.  JOE BABER, CHEMTREC, CURTIS DUGNEY AND BILL WAHL, ASARCO, WERE NOTIFIED OF EXCEPTIONS.

column42: HYDROGEN PEROXIDE, STABILIZED OR HYDROGEN PEROXIDE AQUEOUS SOLUTIONS, STABILIZED WITH MORE THAN 60 PERCENT HYDROGEN PEROXIDE
column168: REGIONAL MGR CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY DEAN L WHITELEY, NOTIFIED BY MANAGER YARD OPERATIONS KEVIN AGUAS, ALBINA YARD, PORTLAND, OR., THAT TANK CAR UTLX 200544, HYDROGEN PEROXIDE, WAS LEAKING.  SWITCH CREW REPORTED PRODUCT LEAKING DOWN SIDE OF CAR AND STARTING SMALL FIRES ON CONTACT WITH RAILROAD TIES.  WHITELEY INSPECTED TANK CAR AND FOUND PRODUCT ON TOP OF THE CONTINUOUS VENT STONE.  CAR WAS ISOLATED AND INSPECTED AM OF SEPTEMBER 9, 19996, OBSERVED PRODUCT HAD NOT FILTERED THROUGH STONE.  CONTACTED TOM HARRISON, DEUGSSA CORP, AND EXPLAINED CIRCUMSTANCES.  HE ADVISED HE WOULD FEDERAL EXPRESS REPLACEMENT FOR VENT STONE.  THAT STONE WAS RECEIVED 1000 HRS SEPT 11, 1996.  STONE WAS INSTALLED AND CAR RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT.

column58: Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Manway or Dome Cover; Piping or Fittings
column168: WHILE MGR CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY C HILL WAS MAKING TANK CAR INSPECTIONS IN NORTH LITTLE ROCK YARD HE OBSERVED LIQUID ON TOP AND SIDES OF TANK CAR DUPX 12404.  MGR HILL'S INSPECTION REVEALED TWO OF EIGHT MANWAY COVER BOLTS LOOSE, WITH MANWAY COVER IN GOOD CONDITION.  SECURED ALL EIGHT MANWAY BOLTS WRENCH TIGHT, WHICH STOPPED LEAK.  REMOVED UNION CARBIDE SEALS 9665 FROM PROTECTIVE HOUSING AND 9666 FROM MANWAY COVER, REPLACED WITH UP SEALS S 799640 AND 41.  NOTIFIED CHEMTREC'S BROOKE WEABER WHO INFORMED SHIPPER REPRESENTATIVE JIM BAILEY OF ABOVE INCIDENT.

column58: Auxiliary Valve; Bottom Outlet Valve; Piping or Fittings
column168: AT 1730 HRS ON 9-9-96, EAST RECEIVING CAR FOREMAN CONTACTED CTS MGR LERCH. HE ADVISED TANK CAR ACFX 200124 LOCATED ON EAST RECEIVING TRACK 3, WAS REPORTED TO BE LEAKING.  UPON ARRIVAL, MGR LERCH NOTED PRODUCT COMING FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE AT A RATE OF APPROXIMATELY 60 DROPS A MINUTE, WITH NO DRAINS OR WATERWAYS IMPACTED.  PRODUCT WAS BEING CONTAINED BY A BUCKET THAT HAD BEEN PLACED BY CAR DEPARTMENT PERSONNEL.  INSPECTION OF CAR BY MGR LERCH REVEALED THAT TOP OPERATED BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE WAS OPEN 3/4 TURN AND THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE CAP WAS LOOSE 1 TURN.  TIGHTENED VALVE AND CAP, WHICH SECURED THE CAR.  NOTIFICATIONS:  1853 HRS, 9-9-96, CHEMTREC, BOB WIBLE, #47615; 1450 HRS, 9-10-96, NEBRASKA, DEQ, GENE WIGGINS, #091096 - GW-1450; 1500 HRS, AMOCO PETROLEUM PRODUCTS, DWAYNE BRUNDAGE, OIL MOVEMENT SHIFT SUPERVISOR.

column58: Auxiliary Valve; Bottom Outlet Valve; Piping or Fittings
column168: ON 091096 AT APPROXIMATELY 1030 AM, MGR CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, GEOFFREY REEDER, WAS ADVISED BY MANAGER TRAIN OPERATIONS, RICHARD WADE, THAT THE RIP TRACK HAD DISCOVERED THIS CAR LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE.  REEDER WAS OUT SO THE HOUSTON FIRE DEPT HAZ MATERIAL TEAM WAS CALLED TO REPAIR THE CAR.  THE TEAM FOUND THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE LEAKING AND NUMEROUS ATTEMPTS TO STOP THE LEAK WERE UNSUCCESSFUL.  THE TEAM INSTALLED A NEW GASKET IN THE OUTLET CAP, WHICH STOPPED THE LEAK.  REEDER SPOKE WITH THE SHIPPER AND REQUESTED THE CAR BE RETURNED TO ORIGIN FOR UNLOADING AND INSPECTION.  THE SHIPPER AGREED TO REEDER'S REQUEST.

column58: Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Manway or Dome Cover; Piping or Fittings
column168: ON 091096 AT APPROXIMATELY 2 PM MGR CHEMICAL TRANS SAFETY, GEOFFREY REEDER, RECEIVED A CALL FROM MGR TRAIN OPERATIONS, RICHARD WADE.  WADE ADVISED THAT THE SWITCH CREW DETECTED AN ODOR WHEN THE CAR PASSED BY THE SWITCH SHANTY.  WADE LOOKED AT THE CAR, BUT DID NOT SEE ANY EVIDENCE OF LEAKAGE NOR DID HE DETECT ANY ODOR.  REEDER ASKED THAT THE CAR BE SET OUT FOR FURTHER INSPECTION.  REEDER FOUND THAT A CROW FOOT FITTING USED TO PRESSURE TEST THE CAR BEFORE SHIPMENT HAD BEEN LEFT IN PLACE.  THIS ALLOWED THE PRODUCT TO SQUIRT OUT OF THE OPEN FITTING WHEN THE CAR WAS MOVED.  THE CROW FOOT FITTING WAS REPLACED WITH THE PLUG THAT WAS RETAINED BY A CHAIN.  THE CAR WAS RELEASED FOR NORMAL MOVEMENT WITHOUT DELAY. CHEMTREC AND THE SHIPPER WERE NOTIFIED.

WHILE CARMAN R V SUDDUTH WAS INSPECTING OUTBOUND TRAIN NOTED STRONG ODOR OF AMMONIA FROM TANK CAR UTLX 99215.  MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY C HILL WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED.  MGR HILL'S INSPECTION REVEALED LIQUID AMMONIA COMING FROM A-END LIQUID VALVE STEM.  CAR EQUIPPED WITH JAMESBURY ANGLE VALVE WHICH HAD TWO LOOSE SCREWS THAT ARE USED TO SECURE PACKING.  MGR HILL TIGHTENED BOTH SCREWS WHICH STOPPED LEAK.  SEAL UP V-31376 WAS REMOVED AND REPLACED WITH SEAL UP S-799642.  CHEMTREC'S JEFF BOTWINICH WAS NOTIFIED AND CONTACTED SHIPPER REPRESENTATIVE BRUCE OWENS ABOUT THE INCIDENT.

WHILE INSPECTOR G G TOMPSON, FEDERAL RAILROAD ADMINISTRATION, WAS CONDUCTING AN INSPECTION, A SLIGHT VAPOR CLOUD WAS OBSERVED IN PROXIMITY TO THE SAFETY VENT ON ACFX 88853.  SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED AND RESPONDED IN A TIMELY MANNER.  SHIPPER'S INSPECTION DETERMINED THAT FRANGIBLE DISK ON SAFETY VENT WAS RUPTURED.  THE SHIPPERED REPLACED FRANGIBLE DISK, CORRECTING INCIDENT.  CARRIER EXERCISED UNREASONABLE USE OF THE ROLLING STOCK.

column42: HYDROGEN PEROXIDE, AQUEOUS SOLUTIONS WITH NOT LESS THAN 20 PERCENT BUT NOT MORE THAN 40 PERCENT HYDROGEN PEROXIDE (STABILIZED AS NECESSARY)
column58: Basic Material; Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug)
column168: PACKAGE WAS BEING HANDLED DURING THE INBOUND PACKAGE SORT WHEN THE DAMAGE WAS DISCOVERED.  THE PACKAGE WAS ISOLATED, OPENED AND EXAMINED TO REVEAL A PLASTIC BOTTLE WITH A LABEL ON IT THAT INDICATED THAT THE MATERIAL WAS HYDROGEN PEROXIDE.  AN MSDS WAS REQUESTED FROM THE SHIPPER AND THE INFORMATION ON THE DOCUMENT VERIFIED THE FACT THAT THE MATERIAL WAS HAZARDOUS AND REGULATED.  THERE WAS A THREE DAY LAG TIME FROM THE TIME THE SHIPMENT WAS DISCOVERED TO THE TIME WE ACTUALLY RECEIVED THE INFORMATION VERIFYING THE FACT THAT IT WAS AN UNDECLARED SHIPMENT.  THERE WERE NO HAZARDOUS MATERIALS MARKING OR LABELS EXHIBITED ON THE PACKAGE NOR WAS THERE A SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS IN ASSOCIATION WITH THE SHIPMENT.  THE SHIPMENT WAS HELD PENDING NOTIFICATION TO THE FAA FOR INVESTIGATION.

column42: HYDROGEN, PEROXIDE, AQUEOUS SOLUTIONS WITH NOT LESS THAN 8 PERCENT BUT LESS THAN 20 PERCENT HYDROGEN PEROXIDE (STABILIZED AS NECESSARY)
column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Defective Component or Device
column168: PACKAGE WAS BEING HANDLED DURING THE OUTBOUND PACKAGE SORT WHEN THE DAMAGE/DISCOVERY OCCURED.  THE PACKAGE WAS TRAVELLING ALONG ONE OF THE SECONDARY CONVEYORS WHEN A DIVERTED PUSHED THE PACKAGE OFF TO ITS DESTINATION SLIDE.  THE ACT OF THIS OCCURANCE APPARENTLY DAMAGED SOME OF THE PLASTIC INNER CONTAINERS IN THE PACKAGE RESULTING IN THE SPILL.  THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED ACCORDING TO PROCEDURE AND TAKEN TO THE DANGEROUS GOODS HOLDING AREA.  UPON CLOSER EXAMINATION IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT THE BOTTLES EXHIBITED LABELS THAT IDENTIFIED THE ITEMS AS SOME TYPE OF HYDROGEN PEROXIDE LIQUID.  THERE WERE NO HAZARDOUS MATERIALS MARKINGS OR LABELS ON THE OUTER  FIBERBOARD BOX NOR WAS THERE A SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS IN EVIDENCE WITH THE PACKAGE.  THE SHIPMENT WAS HELD PENDING NOTIFICATION OF THE F.A.A. FOR INVESTIGATION.

column42: PRINTING INK, FLAMMABLE OR PRINTING INK RELATED MATERIAL (INCLUDING PRINTING INK THINNING OR REDUCING COMPOUND), FLAMMABLE
column168: RON MULLVAN CALLED INFO DISPATCH AND INFORMED THAT A DRUM OF HAZARDOUS MATERIAL HAD A SLIGHT LEAK BUT HE COULD NOT LOCATE THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK. WHEN ARRIVING AT MILPRINT IN LANCASTER, WI, THEY FURTHER INSPECTED THE DRUM THAT STILL COULD NOT FIND THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK IN THE DRUM.  THE DRUM WAS ACCEPTED BY MILPRINT.  ESTIMATED 1 PINT WAS LOST AND EVAPORATED ON TRAILER FLOOR.  PROBABLE CAUSE WAS A DEFECTIVE DRUM.

column62: Abrasion; Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails)
column168: WHILE UNLOADING AT CONSIGNEE, DRIVER NOTICED WET SPOT IN TRAILER, AND DETERMINED IT TO BE ONE DRUM WITH SMALL LEAK.  CONSIGNEE PROVIDED NEUTRALIZING MATERIAL FOR THE TRAILER AND THE SMALL AMOUNT ON GROUND. CONSIGNEE ACCEPTED LEAKING PACKAGE TO BE USED ASAP.  DRIVER BROUGHT TRAILER TO TANKWASH TO REMOVE RESIDUE.

column42: PETROLEUM DISTILLATES, N.O.S. OR PETROLEUM PRODUCTS, N.O.S.
column168: ONE OF TWO - ONE GALLON BOTTLES WAS CRACKED. CONTENTS WERE REPACKED. DAMAGED MATERIALS WERE DISPOSED OF FOLLOWING DMN PROCEDURE.

column58: Basic Material; Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug)
column168: ON 9/19/96 HAZARDOUS MATERIALS TECHNICIAN, WAYNE HOGSETT RESPONDED TO A LEAKING SHIPMENT THAT WAS EMITTING AN ODOR IN THE EXPRESS AREA OF THE MAIN SORT FACILITY OF ABX AIR, INC.  UPON ARRIVAL ON THE SCENE HE FOUND A WHITE PLASTIC ENVELOPE WITH 2 WHITE PLASTIC NON-AEROSOL RECEPTACLES OF "REDKIN SUSPEND FORMING AND MENDING SPRAY".  EACH BOTTLE HAD FLIP TOP CLOSURES AND WAS WRAPPED IN PLASTIC BUBBLE WRAP.  ONE OF THE INNER BOTTLES LEAKED APPROXIMATELY 250 MLS.  EACH BOTTLE STATES "CAUTION FLAMMABLE".  A MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET WAS REQUESTED AND OBTAINED FROM THE SHIPPER. THE MSDS INDICATES THE FLASH POINT TO BE 90 DEGREES F.  THERE WERE NO MARKINGS, LABELS OR PROPER CERTIFICATION ACCOMPANYING THIS SHIPMENT TO INDICATE ITS CONTENTS WERE REGULATED AS HAZ MATS.  THIS SHIPMENT IS AT THE HAZ MAT SORT IN THE SECURITY CAGE, UNDER LOCK AND KEY PENDING INVESTIGATION BY THE FAA.
column172: Plastic container, no capacity or description given

column168: WHILE UNLOADING TRAILER DOCKWORKER DISCOVERED PUNCTURED DRUMS. THE AREA WAS ISOLATED AND PRODUCT IDENTIFIED. EMERGENCY RESPONSE GUIDELINES WERE CONSULTED FOR PROPER CLEANUP AND RECOVERY.
column172: Fiber drum, cont1 for solids, cont2 for liquids

column168: AN UNDERGROUND STORAGE TANK OVERFILLED AND DIESEL FUEL SPILLED ONTO AN ASPHALT PARKING LOT.  THE CUSTOMER, HERTZ, CAUSED THE SPILL BY NOT KNOWING THE SIZE OF THE TANK.  HE ASSURED OUR DRIVER THAT THE TANK WOULD HOLD THE 3000 GALLONS OF DIESEL FUEL WE WERE DELIVERING.  BRENT CROW WAS THE HERTZ REPRESENTATIVE.  ALSO, THE OVERFILLED ALARM DID NOT GO OFF AS IT SHOULD HAVE.  THE SPILL WAS CLEANED UP WITH SPILL PADS AND OIL DRY.  NO DIRT OR WATER WAS CONTAMINATED. WE WILL NOT MAKE ANYMORE DELIVERIES TO THIS LOCATION. THIS WAS THE FIRST AND LAST TIME WE WILL GO TO THIS LOCATION. ALL ABSORBANT MATERIALS ARE DISPOSED OF BY A & D ENVIRONMENTAL IN HIGH POINT, NORTH CAROLINA.

OUR DRIVER WAS INSTRUCTED BY BILLY FAULKNER, A WINN DIXIE EMPLOYEE, TO DROP PRODUCT INTO THE WRONG TANK.  DUE TO THE TANK LOCATION, OUR DRIVER COULD NOT SEE THE TANK OVERFILLED.  IF THE CAPS HAD BEEN ON TIGHT, THE SPILL WOULD HAVE COME OUT THE VENT PIPE WHICH THE DRIVER COULD SEE. SIXTY-TWO (62) GALLONS SPILLED ONTO THE GROUND.  IMMEDIATELY, ABSORBANT MATERIALS WERE PUT OUT TO CONTAIN THE SPILL AND FERGUSON HARBOUR FROM FAIRBURN, GA WAS CALLED TO COMPLETE THE CLEAN UP.  APPROXIMATELY FIVE (5) GALLONS SEEPED INTO A STORM DRAIN.  THREE BOOMS AND ABSORBENT MATERIAL PREVENTED ANY OIL FROM REACHING THE UTPY CREEK.  MICHAEL DERRICK WITH THE GA DEP WAS CALLED AND CAME TO ASSESS THE SITE.  MR. DERRICK HELPED WITH THE CLEAN UP.  FERGUSON HARBOUR WILL DISPOSE OF THE ELEVEN (11) DRUMS OF ABSORBENT MATERIAL CONTAMINATED DURING THE CLEAN UP.  WE WILL NOT DELIVER TO THIS SITE AGAIN DUE TO POOR RECEIVING SITUATION WINN DIXIE HAD.  WE HAVE ADVISED WINN DIXIE TO REPLACE THE BROKEN CAPS ON THEIR TANKS TO PREVENT FUTURE SPILLS.

column42: AEROSOLS, FLAMMABLE, (EACH NOT EXCEEDING 1 L CAPACITY)
column168: DURING THE SORT THE BOXES WERE STRUCK BY OTHER, LARGER PIECES OF FREIGHT. UPON BEING STRUCK THE BOX RIPPED OPEN EXPOSING THE INNER CONTAINERS TO THE SAME PERILS. EIGHT OF THE INNER CONTAINER RECEIVED SOME DAMAGE AND COLLECTIVELY SPILLED APPROXIMATELY ONE-HALF LITRE. THE SPILLED MATERIAL WAS RECOVERED AND PLACED IN A STEEL SALVAGE DRUM. AS SOME OF THE INNER CONTAINERS WERE PRESSURIZED AEROSOL CANS, AND NONE OF THE BOXES EXHIBITED ANY MARKINGS, LABELING, SHIPPING PAPERS, NOR OTHER INDICATOR THAT WOULD LEAD US TO BELIEVE THAT ANY OF THE CONTENTS WERE REGULATED. THE FAA WAS NOTIFIED WHO HAS INSPECTED THE FREIGHT. THE RECIPIENT WILL BE NOTIFIED FOR A DISPOSITION. I SPOKE TO THE RECIPIENT WHEN THE INCIDENT OCCURRED AND SHE EXPLAINED THAT THE PRODUCTS WERE PURCHASED FOR A MARKET PROJECT.

AS DRUM WAS BEING UNLOADED THE BARREL CART ROLLED OVER AN UNEVEN SURFACE BETWEEN THE DOCK PLATE AND THE DOCK.  THE DRUM HAD SLIPPED OFF THE BARRELL CART CAUSING A SMALL PUNCTURE IN THE BOTTOM OF THE PLASTIC. DOCK PERSON INSTRUCTED TO BE MORE CAREFUL WHEN HANDLING HAZARDOUS MATERIAL.

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: ON 9-25-96 LEAD SORTER, RHONDA CLONCH REPORTED A SHIPMENT EMITTING AN ODOR AT THE HAZ MAT SORT FACILITY OF ABX AIR, INC.  I, MICHAEL A. FRYE, HAZ MAT COORDINATOR AND HAZ MAT TECHNICIAN, DONNA RESOR RESPONDED.  UPON ARRIVAL ON THE SCENE THE FIBERBOARD BOX WAS ISOLATED.  TECHNICIAN RESOR DONNED AN ORGANIC VAPOR CARTRIDGE RESPIRATOR TO INVESTIGATE THE INNER CONTENTS. INSIDE WERE FOUR METAL RECEPTACLES WITH SCREW TYPE CLOSURES.  THESE METAL RECEPTACLES HAD A CAPACITY OF 1 LITER EACH.  EACH RECEPTACLE HAD POSITIVE MEANS TO SECURE.  ONE OF THE CLOSURES WAS NOT TIGHTENED PROPERLY WHICH ALLOWED SOME OF THE LIQUID TO LEAK.  THE OTHER FIBERBOARD BOX CONTAINED ONLY ONE METAL RECEPTACLE.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS PROPERLY MARKED LABELED AND PROPER CERTIFICATION ACCOMPANIED.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM AND FORWARDED ONTO ITS DESTINATION.

ON 9/26/96 SORT MANAGER, STEVE MEYER REQUESTED THAT HAZ MAT AREA MANAGER, JIM CURTIS MEET HIM.  UPON ARRIVAL ON THE SCENE SORT MANAGER MEYERS HANDED HAZ MAT AREA MANAGER CURTIS A PLASTIC EXPRESS ENVELOPE.  INSIDE THIS PLASTIC EXPRESS ENVELOPE WERE 8 LITHIUM BATTERIES CONNECTED IN A SERIES. THERE WERE SOME WIRES COMING OFF OF ONE END AND THE OTHER HAD AN EXPOSED CONNECTION.  THESE BATTERIES WERE WRAPPED IN PLASTIC BUBBLE WRAP WHICH WAS NOT SECURED.  WHEN THESE BATTERIES STARTED MOVING AROUND THE WIRES CONNECTED WITH THE EXPOSED CONNECTION CAUSING THEM TO ARC.  THIS CAUSED THE PLASTIC ENVELOPE TO BURN ALONG WITH THE OUTER PLASTIC BAG.  THIS CAUSED A BURN HOLE IN BOTH PIECES.  THERE WERE NO MARKINGS LABELS OR PROPER CERTIFICATION ACCOMPANYING THIS SHIPMENT TO INDICATE ITS CONTENTS WERE REGULATED AS HAZ MAT.  THIS SHIPMENT IS AT THE HAZ MAT SORT IN THE SECURITY CAGE UNDER LOCK AND KEY PENDING INVESTIGATION BY THE FAA.

FRYE, HAZ MAT COORDINATOR AND HAZ MAT TECHNICIAN, THEO GHOSTSTONE RESPONDED.  UPON ARRIVAL ON THE SCENE TECHNICIAN GHOSTSTONE DONNED A SELF CONTAINED BREATHING APPARATUS AND AN ENCAUPSULATED SUIT. THERE WERE NO LABELS OR PROPER CERTIFICATION ACCOMPANYING THIS SHIPMENT TO INDICATE ITS CONTENTS WERE REGULATED AS HAZ MAT.  THIS SHIPMENT IS AT THE HAZ MAT SORT IN THE SECURITY CAGE, UNDER LOCK AND KEY, PENDING INVESTIGATION BY THE FAA.

AT COMPLETION OF UNLOADING PROCESS, DRIVER WAS TOLD BY CUSTOMER RECEIVER PERSON TO SHUT DOWN THE TRUCK VALVE. AT TIME DRIVER SHUT DOWN THE TRUCK VALVE, THE CUSTOMER'S UNLOADING HOSE BURST. APPROXIMATELY 10 GALLONS OF PRODUCT WAS SPILLED. CUSTOMER AND DRIVER PUT DOWN ABSORBENT MATERIAL TO CONTAIN SPILL. SOME OF THE PRODUCT SPRAYED ONTO THE TRACTOR CAB AND PAINT WAS DAMAGED. THE QUANTITY (10 GALLONS) IS OUR DRIVER'S ESTIMATE. WE HAVE BEEN UNABLE TO THIS DATE TO GET A COMMENT FROM CUSTOMER WITH CALLS TO JEFF GROAT, OCCIDENTAL SAFETY DEPT. 419-675-5300 - DRIVER WAS UNDER IMPRESSION CUSTOMER PERSONNEL WOULD CLEAN UP SPILL. HE WAS RELEASED FROM AREA BEFORE THIS WAS DONE.

WHEN A DOCKMAN ENTERED THE TRAILER TO LOAD HIS FREIGHT, HE NOTICED A DRUM LEAKING. THE HOLE IN THE DRUM WAS CAUSED WHEN SOMEONE PUT SKIDS ON TOP OF THE DRUMS. THE FORKLIFT PUNCTURED A HOLE IN THE DRUM. THE DRUM WAS REMOVED FROM THE TRAILER (SFVZ-210729) AND PUT INTO A RECOVERY DRUM. THE DRUM IS BEING HELD ON THE CGI DOCK PENDING DISPOSITION FROM THE SHIPPER. CLEANUP WAS DONE BY DOCKMAN, J.J. SCHERP.

MANAGER CTS RICHARD TUFTS NOTIFIED BY PHONE THAT CAR GATX 44861 HAD PRODUCT LEAKING FROM FRANGIBLE DISC.  MANAGER TUFTS CONTACTED SHIPPER WHO ADVISED THAT DISC WOULD BE REPLACED BY INDUSTRY PERSONNEL.  NO FURTHER ACTION REQUIRED BY RAILROAD.  THIS REPORT ALSO COVERS SECOND CAR REPORTED ON CHEMTREC EMERGENCY REPORT #47906 AS GATX  44087 WITH SIMILAR PROBLEMS.  RECORDS SEARCH DOES NOT IDENTIFY THIS CAR AS THE PROPER NUMBER AND SHIPPER/CONSIGNEE HOWEVER THE REPORT IS CORRECT IN STATING THAT TWO CARS SHIPPED FROM ROSEPORT, MN, BY KOCH INDUSTRIES SUSTAINED FAILURE OF THE FRANGIBLE DISCS AND BOTH WERE REPAIRED BY THE CONSIGNEE AT PROVISO YARD. BOTH CARS CONTAINED THE SAME PRODUCT, SULFURIC ACID, SPENT.  COPY OF CHEMTREC REPORT IS ON FILE WITH THIS REPORT AT MANAGER TUFTS OFFICE IN ST. LOUIS.

ON SEPTEMBER 9, 1996, EM TECH RECEIVED THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE CALL AT APPROXIMATELY 1600 HRS. EM TECH LOADED AND MOBILIZED A RESPONSE CREW TO THE GRAPEVINE, TEXAS FACILITY. THE CREW RESPONDED WITH ALL NECESSARY SUPPLIES AND EQUIPMENT TO RECTIFY THE AFOREMENTIONED INCIDENT. UPON ARRIVAL, EM TECH PERSONNEL MET WITH MR. BRETT TRENT AND THE GRAPEVINE FIRE DEPARTMENT FOR AN INCIDENT BRIEFING. IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT THE LEAKING DRUM HAS BEEN PUNCTURED DURING THE LOADING PROCESS AND HAD LEAKED APPROXIMATELY THIRTY (30) GALLONS. THE DRUM WAS LOCATED AT THE REAR OF THE TRAILER AND LEAKED MOST OF ITS CONTENT TO THE NOSE OF THE TRAILER LEAVING APPROXIMATELY TWO INCHES OF PRODUCT AT THE FRONT. THE ENTIRE TRAILER WAS UNLOADED USING EMO TRANS' FORKLIFT. AFTER UNLOADING THE TRAILER, OIL DRY ABSORBENT WAS USED TO SOAK UP THE FREE STANDING MATERIAL. AFTER THE MATERIAL WAS SWEPT UP AND PLACED INTO DRUMS FOR DISPOSAL, A LIGHT SOLUTION OF SULFAMIC ACID WAS USED TO NEUTRALIZE ANYTHING THAT WAS LEFT ON THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER. ABSORBENT WAS ALSO USED ON THE GROUND WHERE THE PRODUCT HAD LEAKED THROUGH THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER AND ONTO THE CONCRETE. THE TWO (2) DRUMS OF WASTE GENERATED WERE PLACED IN THE EMO TRANS WAREHOUSE PENDING THE DISPOSAL AND PICKUP OF THE DRUMS BY THE EMTECH DISPOSAL DEPARTMENT.
